# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bugatti-veyron
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bugatti-veyron/1939-24-hours-of-le-mans] The **1939 24 Hours of Le Mans** (French: ***24 Heures du Mans 1939***) was the 16th Grand Prix of Endurance, and took place at Circuit de la Sarthe, Le Mans, France, on 17 and 18 June 1939.
[src:bugatti-veyron/1939-24-hours-of-le-mans] The 1939 programme cover depicted the raising of six nations' flags: France, Italy, Great Britain (its civil Red Ensign), Belgium, Germany, and the United States.
[src:bugatti-veyron/1939-24-hours-of-le-mans] By June 1939, the outbreak of World War II was less than three months away.
[src:bugatti-veyron/1939-24-hours-of-le-mans] The following year's 24 Hours of Le Mans was originally planned for June 1940, but due to the invasion of France in May the race was called off.
[src:bugatti-veyron/1939-24-hours-of-le-mans] Endurance racing would not return to Le Mans until 1949, four years after V-E day ended World War II in Europe.
[src:bugatti-veyron/1939-24-hours-of-le-mans] Class winners are denoted with **bold**.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The **24 Hours of Le Mans** (French: ***24 Heures du Mans***; French pronunciation: [vɛ̃t.katʁ‿œʁ dy mɑ̃]) is an endurance sports car race held annually near the city of Le Mans, France.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] First run in 1923, it is the oldest active endurance racing event in the world and is widely considered one of the world's most prestigious races.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It is part of two informal "Triple Crown" series: the Triple Crown of Motorsport (with the F1 Monaco Grand Prix and the Indianapolis 500) and the Triple Crown of endurance racing (with the Florida-based 24 Hours of Daytona and 12 Hours of Sebring).
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Unlike fixed-distance races whose winner is determined by minimum time, the 24 Hours of Le Mans is won by the car that covers the greatest distance in 24 hours.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The cars on this track are able to achieve speeds of 366 km/h (227 mph), and reached 407 km/h (253 mph) on the main straight in 1988 – instigating the addition of more chicanes to the track to reduce speed reached.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Racing teams must balance the demands of speed with the cars' ability to run for 24 hours without mechanical failure.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race is organized by the Automobile Club de l'Ouest (ACO).
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It is held on the Circuit de la Sarthe, composed of closed public roads and dedicated sections of a racing track.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 24 Hours of Le Mans was often part of the World Sportscar Championship from 1953 until that series' final season in 1992.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2011, it was a part of the Intercontinental Le Mans Cup.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2012, the race has been a part of the FIA World Endurance Championship.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A 10-hour American version of the race, called Petit Le Mans, has been held annually since 1998.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The most recent running of the event, the 94th 24 Heures du Mans, ran from 13 to 14 June 2026.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Launched when Grand Prix motor racing was the dominant form of motorsport throughout Europe, Le Mans was designed to present a different test.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Instead of focusing on the ability of a car company to build the fastest machines, the 24 Hours of Le Mans would concentrate on the ability of manufacturers to build sporty yet reliable cars.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This encouraged innovation in producing reliable and fuel-efficient vehicles, because endurance racing requires cars that last and spend as little time in the pits as possible.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the same time, the layout of the track required cars with better aerodynamics and stability at high speeds.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] While this was shared with Grand Prix racing, few tracks in Europe had straights of a length comparable to the *Ligne droite des Hunaudières*, often referred to as Mulsanne Straight after the village it leads to.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The oil crisis in the early 1970s led organizers to adopt a fuel economy formula known as Group C that limited the amount of fuel each car was allowed.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although it was later abandoned, fuel economy remains important as new fuel sources reduce the time spent during pit stops.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Such technological innovations have had a trickle-down effect and can be incorporated into consumer cars.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This has also led to faster and more exotic supercars as manufacturers seek to develop faster road cars in order to develop them into even faster GT cars.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In the 2000s, hybrid systems (flywheel, super-capacitor, battery coupled with both petrol and diesel) have been championed in the Le Mans prototype category as rules have been changed to their benefit and to further push efficiency.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race is held in mid-June, near the summer solstice, meaning the shortest night and very hot conditions for drivers, particularly in closed vehicles with poor ventilation.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race begins in mid-afternoon and finishes the following day at the same hour the race started the previous day.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2025 race attracted 332,000 spectators.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Modern competitors often cover well over 5,000 km (3,110 mi).
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The record is 2010's 5,410 km (3,360 mi), more than six times the length of the Indianapolis 500 (500 mi or 805 km), or about 18 times longer than a Formula One *Grand Prix*.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Drivers and their teams strive for speed and avoiding mechanical damage, as well as managing the cars' consumables – primarily fuel, tires, and braking materials.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It also tests endurance, with drivers frequently racing for over two hours before a relief driver can take over during a pit stop while eating and resting.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Current regulations mandate that three drivers share each competing vehicle, with individual limits of driving no more than 4 hours in a 6-hour period, and no more than 14 hours total.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Competing teams race in groups called "classes", or cars of similar specification, while competing simultaneously for outright placing amongst all classes.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Originally, the race showcased cars as they were sold to the general public, then called "Sports Cars", in contrast with the specialised racing cars used in Grand Prix motor racing.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Over time, the competing vehicles evolved away from their publicly available road car roots.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] These are further broken down into: Hypercar (LMH or LMDh), LMP2 and LMGT3 (GT cars).
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race was part of the World Sportscar Championship every year from its inception in 1953 until its demise in 1992, except during the 1956, 1975–1979 and 1989–1990 seasons.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2011, the race was part of the Intercontinental Le Mans Cup, and since 2012 it has been part of the FIA World Endurance Championship.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, winning Le Mans is often considered to be more important than winning the championship itself.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race is also known as a leg of the informal Triple Crown of Motorsport which links Formula One, IndyCar, and sports car racing to represent a career achievement for drivers.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Additionally, it is seen as a leg of the Triple Crown of endurance racing, which links the three largest sports car races together, with the 24 Hours of Daytona and 12 Hours of Sebring forming the other legs.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 1998, an endurance race called "Petit Le Mans" has been held every year as a 10-hour American version of the Le Mans 24 Hours.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] From 1999 to 2013, Petit Le Mans was part of the American Le Mans Series along with the 12 Hours of Sebring.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2014, the IMSA SportsCar Championship (a merger of ALMS and the Rolex Sports Car Series) has held all four major American endurance classics, which teams can use to prepare for racing at Le Mans.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Each car was required to have at least two seats.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, recently cars only need to have space to accommodate a second seat in the cockpit rather than the seat itself.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Two doors are allowed; open-cockpit cars do not require doors.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2014, all cars in the premier LMP1 category must have a roof for safety; open-cockpit cars are only permitted in the slightly slower LMP2 category.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2017, all prototype cars—Hypercar or LMP2—must have closed cockpits.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although all cars compete at the same time, as of 2021, there are separate classes.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A prize is awarded to the winner of each class and the overall winner.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The number of classes has varied over the years, but there are now three: Hypercar, LMP2, and LMGT3.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Successor to the Le Mans Prototype 1 (LMP1) is the custom-built Hypercar (LMH or LMDh) class.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It is the top class and debuted in 2021.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The new technical regulations are intended to prevent cost escalations while enabling greater variety in technical approaches and car aesthetics.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This is followed by the LMP2 class where teams are obliged to run one of four approved chassis – ORECA, Ligier, Dallara, or Multimatic/Riley – mated with a standard 4.2-litre Gibson V8 engine.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] ORECA is the most commonly used LMP2 chassis.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] LMP1 teams are not subjected to chassis and engine restrictions.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Their extra power, lower weight, and more complex aerodynamics result in much quicker lap times; LMP1 cars also may use hybrid technology.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The next class is LMGT3, which are similar to production-based sports cars.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Concept cars intended to test new automotive technologies may participate in the race under the "Garage 56" banner.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Such entries are classified in the race results, though are not expected to be competitive as their sole focus is to demonstrate experimental features.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Initially, there were no rules on the number of car drivers or how long they could drive.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although almost all teams used two drivers in the early decades, some Le Mans drivers such as Pierre Levegh and Eddie Hall attempted to run the race solo, hoping to save time by not having to change drivers.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Until the 1980s, there were teams in which only two drivers competed, but by the end of the decade, the rules were changed to stipulate that at least three drivers must drive each car.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] By the 1990s, due to the speeds of the cars and the strain it puts on drivers, additional rules to reduce driver fatigue mandated that drivers could not drive for over 240 minutes (over 4 hours) and that no one driver could run for over 840 minutes (14 hours) total.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With careful management of driver stints, this makes it possible to complete the race with only two drivers (as Jeroen Bleekemolen and Cooper MacNeil did in 2014), although the vast majority of teams still continue to use three drivers.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2017, the driving time rules were further changed.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] If necessary, officials may require a drive time limit of 80 minutes of consecutive time behind the wheel and a minimum 30-minute rest break.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The rule applies only if the air temperature is at least 32 °C (89.6 °F).
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although it has been a part of the World Sportscar Championship for most of its existence, the race has had different regulations for safety and competition reasons partly due to its length.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] For many decades, cars had to run at least an hour into the race before they could refill fluids for the car, such as oil or coolant, except for fuel.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This was an attempt by the ACO to help increase efficiency and reliability.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Those who could not last the first hour without replacing lost fluids risked disqualification.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Another rule unique to Le Mans is that cars must be switched off while refueling in the pits.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Not only is this safer and less of a fire hazard, but it is also another test of reliability, demanding a guaranteed ability to restart many times under race conditions.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Another element of this rule is that mechanics are not allowed to work on the car while it is being refuelled (other than helping a driver in or out of the car), which has led teams to adapt innovative ways to decrease the time of these lengthy pit stops.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Drivers can get out of the car and be replaced by another driver during refuelling.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Those rules are also applied in the FIA World Endurance Championship.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] There are various long-standing traditions at Le Mans, including the waving of the French tricolor to start the race.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This is usually preceded by a fly-over featuring jets trailing blue, white, and red smoke.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A similar flag tradition is track marshals waving safety flags during the race's final lap, congratulating the winners and other finishers.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Le Mans was the venue for the first televised instance of a winning driver celebrating by spraying champagne instead of drinking it.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] When Dan Gurney won the 1967 race with co-driver A.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Foyt, the two drivers mounted the victory podium, and Gurney was handed a magnum of champagne.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Looking down, he saw Ford CEO Henry Ford II, team owner Carroll Shelby and their wives, as well as several journalists who had predicted disaster for the high-profile duo.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Gurney shook the bottle and sprayed everyone nearby.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Gurney autographed and gave the bottle of champagne to *Life* photographer Flip Schulke, who used it as a lamp for years before returning it to Gurney.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race has been cancelled ten times: in 1936 (a labour strike during the Great Depression) and between 1940 and 1948 (World War II).
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race usually takes place on the second weekend of June, with qualifying and practice taking place on the Wednesday and Thursday before the race, following a car inspection on Monday and Tuesday.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Currently, these sessions are held in the evening, with two separate two-hour sessions held each night.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Friday serves as a day of rest, and a parade of all the drivers through Le Mans is held.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Test days held at the end of April or beginning of May served as a pre-qualification weeding out the slowest cars.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, in 2005 the exorbitant cost of transporting cars to and from Le Mans led organizers to move the test day to the first weekend of June.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Pre-qualification was eliminated in 2000, meaning that all competitors invited to the test would be allowed into the race.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2001 the Le Mans Legend races have mostly been part of the schedule, usually running exhibition races during qualifying days, a few hours prior to the sessions for the Le Mans entrants.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since its inception, the race has usually started at 4:00 p.m. local time (Central European Summer Time, UTC + 02:00) on Saturday.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Initially, the car that covered the greatest distance from its starting position was the winner.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This is known to have caught out the Ford team in 1966.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With a dominant 1–2 lead, the two cars slowed to allow for a photo opportunity at the finish line, with Ken Miles slightly ahead of Bruce McLaren.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, since McLaren's car had started much farther back on the grid than Miles's, McLaren's car had covered the greatest distance over the 24 hours.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With the margin of victory determined to be eight metres, McLaren and his co-driver, Chris Amon, were declared the winners.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The decision cost Miles and Denny Hulme a victory.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Miles had already won the other two endurance races at Sebring and Daytona.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With a win at Le Mans, he would have become the first man to win all three and the first to win them all in the same year.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The "greatest distance" rule was modified with the introduction of a rolling start in 1971.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Now, the car that completes the greatest distance as of the final lap's completion – where "greatest distance" is measured by the start/finish line for all competitors – wins.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] When two cars finish the same number of laps, their finishing order is determined by the faster overall completion time.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This rule was used in the 2011 24 Hours of Le Mans to determine the race winner.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The top two finishers completed 355 laps, with only 13 seconds difference between them.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although "greatest distance run" determines the provisional order of finishers, additional requirements must be met for a car to be classified.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] All classification requirements hold except in exceptional circumstances, as determined by the race stewards.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race traditionally began with what became known as the *Le Mans start*, in which cars were lined up along the length of the pits.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Until 1962, cars lined up by engine capacity.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Beginning in 1963, qualifying times determined the lineup.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The starting drivers stood on the opposite side of the front stretch.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] When the French flag dropped to signify the start, the drivers ran across the track, entered and started their cars without assistance, and drove away.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This became a safety issue in the late 1960s when some drivers ignored their safety harnesses, then a recent invention.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This led to drivers running the first few laps either improperly harnessed due to attempting to do it while driving or sometimes not even harnessed at all, leading to several deaths when cars were involved in accidents due to the bunched field at the start.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This starting method inspired Porsche to locate the ignition key switch to the left of the steering wheel.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In a left-hand drive car, this allowed the driver to use his left hand to start the engine and his right hand to put the transmission into gear, which in turn shaves off a few tenths of a second.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Stirling Moss developed another method for speeding up the start.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] His car was waiting with first gear already engaged.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] He switched the starter on when he jumped in without depressing the clutch.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The starter motor immediately jerked the car forward, but the engine did not start due to low RPM.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After a few seconds of motion, he pushed the clutch down, allowing the engine to speed up and start while the car was moving.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Feeling the Le Mans Start was unsafe, in the 1969 race, Jacky Ickx opposed it by walking across the track while his competitors ran.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although he was nearly hit by a faster competitor's car while walking, Ickx took the time to fasten his safety belts before pulling away.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Privateer John Woolfe died in an accident on the first lap of that race; Ickx won.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The traditional Le Mans start was changed for 1970.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Cars were still lined up along the pit wall, but the drivers were already inside and strapped in.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the dropping of the French tricolor, the drivers started their engines and drove away.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 1971, a rolling start (sometimes known as an *Indianapolis start*) begins the race.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] While the cars do still start out lined up against the pit wall, when the green flag is waved the cars pull away one by one to begin a formation lap behind the safety car; when that car returns to the pit lane, the starter waves the French flag to start the race.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The circuit on which the 24 Hours of Le Mans is run is named the Circuit de la Sarthe, after the department that Le Mans is within.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It consists of both permanent track and public roads temporarily closed for the race.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 1923, the track has been extensively modified, mostly for safety reasons, and now is 13.626 km (8.467 mi) in length.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although it initially entered the town of Le Mans, the track was cut short to better protect spectators.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This led to the creation of the Dunlop Curve and Tertre Rouge corners before rejoining the old circuit on the Mulsanne Straight.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Another major change was on the Mulsanne itself in 1990 when the FIA decreed that it would no longer sanction any circuit that had a straight longer than 2 km (1.2 mi).
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] To comply with this, two chicanes were added to the 6-kilometre-long (3.7 mi) straight, dividing it into three pieces about 2 km each.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The addition of the chicanes was further influenced by the fact that the speed of Welter Racing's WM P88, driven by French driver Roger Dorchy, had been timed at 407 km/h (253 mph) during the 1988 race.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This was the record speed before the addition of the chicanes.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Due to the shorter length of the straights, the speed record at Le Mans now, after the introduction of the chicanes, is 366 km/h (227 mph).
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Typically race cars achieve top speed of just under 320 km/h (200 mph) at the current track (with chicanes).
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The public sections of the track differ from the permanent circuit, especially in comparison with the Bugatti Circuit which is inside the Circuit de la Sarthe.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Due to heavy traffic, the public roads are not as smooth or well kept.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] They also offer less grip because of the lack of soft-tyre rubber laid down from racing cars, though this only affects the first few laps of the race.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The roads are closed only within a few hours of the practice sessions and the race before being opened again almost as soon as the race is finished.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Workers have to assemble and dismantle safety barriers every year for the public sections.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 24 Hours of Le Mans was first run on 26 and 27 May 1923, through public roads around Le Mans.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Originally planned to be a three-year event, as part of the Rudge-Whitworth Triennial Cup, with a winner being declared by the car which could go the farthest distance over three consecutive 24-hour races, this idea was abandoned in 1928.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Overall winners were declared for every year depending on who covered the furthest distance by the time 24 hours were up.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The early races were dominated by French, British, and Italian drivers, teams, and cars, with Bugatti, Bentley, and Alfa Romeo being the top brands.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Innovations in car design began appearing at the track in the late 1930s, with Bugatti and Alfa Romeo running highly aerodynamic bodywork to run down the Mulsanne Straight at faster speeds.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race was cancelled in 1936 due to general strikes in France, and the outbreak of World War II in 1939 resulted in a ten-year hiatus.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Following the reconstruction of circuit facilities, the race was resumed in 1949 with renewed interest from major automobile manufacturers.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 1949 was also Ferrari's first victory, the 166MM of Luigi Chinetti and Peter Mitchell-Thomson.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After the formation of the World Sportscar Championship in 1953, of which Le Mans was a part, Ferrari, Aston Martin, Mercedes-Benz, Jaguar and many others began sending multiple cars backed by their respective factories to compete for overall wins against their competitors.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This competitiveness sometimes resulted in tragedy, as in the 1955 Le Mans disaster during the 1955 race in which Pierre Levegh's car crashed into a crowd of spectators, killing more than 80 people.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The incident led to the widespread introduction of safety measures, not only at the circuit but elsewhere in the motorsport world.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The entire pit complex was razed and rebuilt further back following the accident, allowing the pit straight to be widened.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, there was still no barrier between the track and the pit lane.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Safety standards improved, but the cars got faster.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The move from open-cockpit roadsters to closed-cockpit coupés resulted in speeds of over 320 km/h (200 mph) on the Mulsanne.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Ford entered the picture with the GT40, finally ending Ferrari's dominance with four straight wins (1966–1969) before the 1960s ended and the cars and the race changed substantially.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In those years racing took a turn towards more extreme speeds and automotive designs.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This contributed to the replacement of the typical standing *Le Mans start* with a rolling *Indianapolis start*.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Purpose-built sportscars became the norm, with the traditional production-based cars now racing in lower classes.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Porsche was dominant throughout the decade with their 917, 935, and 936 models.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] French manufacturers Matra-Simca and Renault also gained success, with the first victories for the nation since the 1950 race.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Notably, 1978 saw the first win of a turbocharged engine with the Renault Alpine A443.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The decade is also remembered for strong performances from many privateer constructors, with two scoring the only victories for a privateer in the decade.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] John Wyer's Mirage won in 1975, while Jean Rondeau's self-titled chassis took 1980.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The rest of the 1980s was known for the dominance by Porsche under the new Group C race car formula that encouraged fuel efficiency.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Originally running the effective 956, it was later replaced by the 962.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Both chassis were affordable enough for privateers to purchase them en masse, leading to the two model types winning six years in a row.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Jaguar and Mercedes-Benz returned to sports car racing, with Jaguar being the first to break Porsche's dominance with victories in 1988 and 1990 (with the XJR-9 and Jaguar XJR-12 respectively).
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Mercedes-Benz won in 1989, with what was seen as the latest incarnation of the elegant "Silver Arrows", the Sauber C9, while an influx of Japanese manufacturer interest saw prototypes from Nissan and Toyota.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In qualifying for the 1988 race, a WM Peugeot – built for speed, not meant to (and it did not) endure 24 hours – set the never surpassed speed trap record of 407 km/h (253 mph) in the *Ligne Droite des Hunaudières*, famous for its 6 km (3.7 mi) long straight.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Mazda would be the first Japanese manufacturer to succeed, with their unique rotary-powered 787B winning in 1991.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 1992 and 1993, Peugeot dominated the race with its Peugeot 905 as the Group C formula and World Sportscar Championship were fading in participation.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The circuit would also undergo one of its most notable changes in 1990, when the 5 km long Mulsanne was modified to include two chicanes in order to stop speeds of more than 400 km/h (250 mph) from being reached again.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This began the ACO's trend to slow the cars on various portions of the track.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, speeds over 320 km/h (200 mph) are still regularly reached at various points on a lap.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Following the demise of the World Sportscar Championship, Le Mans saw a resurgence of production-based grand tourer cars.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Thanks to a loophole in the rules, Porsche succeeded in convincing the ACO that a Dauer 962 Le Mans supercar was a production car, allowing Porsche to race their Porsche 962 for one final time, dominating the field.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although the ACO attempted to close the loophole for 1995, newcomer McLaren would win the race in their supercar's first appearance thanks to the reliability of the BMW V12 powered F1 GTR, beating faster yet more trouble-prone prototypes.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The trend would continue through the 1990s as more exotic supercars were built in order to skirt the ACO's rules regarding production-based race cars, leading to Porsche, Mercedes-Benz, Toyota, Nissan, Panoz, and Lotus entering the GT categories.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This culminated in the 1999 event, in which these GT cars were faced with the Le Mans Prototypes of BMW, Audi, Toyota and Ferrari.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] BMW would survive with the victory, their first and only overall Le Mans win to date.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the same time, Mercedes left sportscar racing indefinitely following three catastrophic though non-fatal crashes stemming from severe aerodynamic flaws with their CLR.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This strong manufacturer influence led the ACO to lend the Le Mans name to a sports car series in the United States in 1999, known as the American Le Mans Series, which ran until the end of the 2013 season after which it merged with Grand-Am to form the United SportsCar Championship.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Many major automobile manufacturers withdrew from sports car racing after 1999 due to the high cost.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Only Cadillac and Audi remained, and Audi easily dominated with the R8.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Cadillac pulled out three years later, and attempts by Panoz, Chrysler, and MG to beat Audi all fell short.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After three victories in a row, Audi provided engine, team staff, and drivers to Bentley, a corporate partner, which had returned in 2001.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2003, the factory Bentley Speed 8s beat privateer Audis.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The Chevrolet Corvette Racing Team and their C5-R won several times in the GTS class, finishing 1st and 2nd in 2001, 2002, and 2004.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] They finished 2nd and 3rd in 2003 behind Ferrari.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the end of 2005, after five overall victories for the R8, and six to its V8 turbo engine, Audi took on a new challenge by introducing a diesel engined prototype known as the R10 TDI.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although not the first diesel to race, it was the first to win at Le Mans.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This era saw other alternative fuel sources used, including bio-ethanol.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the same time, Peugeot decided to follow Audi's lead and pursue a diesel entry in 2007 with their 908 HDi FAP.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In the 2008 race between the Audi R10 TDI and the Peugeot 908 HDi FAP, the Audi won by a margin of fewer than 10 minutes.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] For the 2009 24 Hours of Le Mans, Peugeot introduced a new energy-recovery system similar to the KERS used in Formula One.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Aston Martin entered the LMP1 category, but still raced in GT1 with private teams.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi returned with the new R15 TDI, but Peugeot prevailed in its first overall win since 1993.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2010 running reaffirmed the race as a test of endurance and reliability.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Peugeot chose overall speed in adjusting their cars and engines to adhere to the 2010 regulations, while Audi chose reliability.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] All four Peugeots had retired at the end of the race, three due to engine failure, while Audi finished 1–2–3.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2011 and 2012 races were marred by a series of accidents.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2011, the Audi driven by Allan McNish crashed heavily in the first hour, barrel rolling into a tire wall shortly after the Dunlop Bridge.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At night, the defending race-winning Audi driven by Mike Rockenfeller crashed similarly between the Mulsanne and Indianapolis corners.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Neither driver was seriously injured, nor were any spectators.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The third Audi entry was driven by Marcel Fässler, André Lotterer, and Benoît Tréluyer won the race.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2012 race saw two factory Toyotas replace Peugeot, which had withdrawn earlier, but one flipped at Mulsanne Corner.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Driver Anthony Davidson suffered two broken vertebrae but could exit the car himself.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Shortly after sunset, the other Toyota retired with mechanical difficulties, leading to another Audi victory.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2011, the race became the premier round of the Intercontinental Le Mans Cup, attempting to make a world championship for endurance racing again.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2012, the race became the centerpiece of the FIA World Endurance Championship, the successor to the ILMC.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2012 event was the first time the race was won by a hybrid electric vehicle, which was the Audi R18 e-tron quattro.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Regulations were changed for 2014, notably with a requirement that all LMP1 cars must be closed-cockpit, some changes to the hybrid system, and the introduction of the slow zone system.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Porsche returned to Le Mans in 2014 with a new factory LMP1 program, and Nissan returned to run an LMP1 program in 2015.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi withdrew from racing at the 24 Hours of Le Mans in 2016 and Nissan after only one attempt in 2015.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Porsche won the race in 2015, 2016, and 2017 with its hybrid 919, and remains the most successful manufacturer at Le Mans, with 19 overall victories.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2017, changes were made to the LMP2 regulations on cockpit and chassis, meaning all prototype cars must be closed-cockpit.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2018, Toyota won their first Le Mans with Fernando Alonso, Sébastien Buemi and Kazuki Nakajima driving.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 2020 also saw the race held behind closed doors for the first time due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 2021 saw the introduction of the Hypercar class, a class that allows for Le Mans Hypercars and from 2023 onwards also LMDh cars to participate.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 2021 saw the race postponed once again, this time until August.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] For 2021 and 2022, non-hybrid LMP1 cars were allowed to participate as "grandfathered" LMP1 cars, although only Alpine would make use of this.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Other entries in the hypercar class were Toyota and privateer team Glickenhaus.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The new Hypercar regulations allowed manufacturers more freedom with the design, leading to cars such as the wingless Peugeot 9X8 entering in 2022, with other unique designs expected to be added.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The LMP2 regulations were extended to 2027 with the next generation LMP2 cars to be introduced in 2028.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 2028 will likely also see the introduction of hydrogen powered prototypes.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The former LMGTE class was also replaced by LMGT3 in 2024.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Le Mans has seen many innovations in automotive design to counteract the circuit's difficulties.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] These have either been dictated by rules or have been attempts by manufacturers to outwit the competition.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Some innovations were incorporated into the everyday automobile.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] One of the keys to Le Mans is top speed due to the long straights that dominate the circuit.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This has meant cars have attempted to achieve the maximum speeds possible instead of relying on downforce for the turns.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] While early competitors' cars were street cars with their bodywork removed to reduce weight, innovators like Bugatti developed cars that saw the beginnings of aerodynamics.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Nicknamed *tanks* due to their similarity to military tanks in World War I, these cars used simple curves to cover all the car's mechanical elements and increase top speed.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Once Le Mans returned after World War II, most manufacturers would adopt closed bodies streamlined for better aerodynamics.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A notable example of the changes brought about by aerodynamics are the 1950 entries by Briggs Cunningham.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Cunningham entered two 1950 Cadillac Coupe de Villes, one nearly stock and the other completely rebodied in a streamlined aluminum shape developed by Grumman Aircraft Engineering Corporation that looked so unusual that it was nicknamed "Le Monstre" by the French press.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The smoothing of body shapes and fairing-in of various parts of the machine brought about by the continual search for reduction of aerodynamic drag led to a separation from Grand Prix cars, which rarely had large bodywork.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] As the years went on, bodywork became all-enveloping, while at the same time lighter.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The larger bodywork with spoilers was able to provide more downforce for the turns without increasing the drag, allowing cars to maintain high speeds.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Extended bodywork would usually concentrate on the car's rear, usually being termed *long tail*.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The bodywork also began to cover the cockpit for less drag.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, open cockpits would come and go over the years as rules varied.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Aerodynamics reached its peak in 1989 before the Mulsanne Straight was modified.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] During the 1988 race, the crew of a Peugeot powered WM prototype taped over the engine openings, allowing Roger Dorchy to set a recorded speed of 407 km/h (253 mph) down the Mulsanne.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, the car was almost undrivable elsewhere on the circuit.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The engine was soon destroyed from a lack of cooling.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, for the 1989 event, the Mercedes-Benz C9 reached 400 km/h (249 mph) under qualifying conditions.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A wide variety of engines have competed at Le Mans in attempts to achieve greater speed and fuel economy and to spend less time in the pits.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Engine sizes have also varied greatly, with the smallest engines being a mere 569 cc (Simca Cinq) and the largest upwards of 8,000 cc (SRT Viper GTS-R).
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Supercharging was an early innovation for increasing output, first being raced in 1929, while turbocharging first appeared in 1974.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The first entry without a piston engine came in 1963, when Rover partnered with British Racing Motors to run a gas turbine car with mixed success, an effort they repeated in 1965.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The American Howmet Corporation attempted to employ a turbine in 1968 with even less success: although the engines offered great power, they were hot and not fuel-efficient.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Another non-piston engine that appeared was the Wankel engine, otherwise known as the rotary engine.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Used exclusively (in automotive applications) by Mazda since its introduction in 1970, the compact rotary engine suffered from fuel economy problems, yet eventually achieved the success that the turbines had not.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After many years of development, Mazda finally became the only winner of the race not to have a piston-powered engine, as it took the 1991 event with the 787B.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Alternative fuel sources have also played a part in more normal engine designs, with the first non-gasoline car appearing in 1949.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The Delettrez Special was powered by a diesel engine.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In contrast, a second diesel appeared in the form of the M.A.P. the following year.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although diesel was used on several occasions, it was not until 2006 that a prominent manufacturer, Audi, invested in diesel; the company's R10 TDI was a success.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Ethanol fuel appeared in 1980 in a modified Porsche 911, leading to a class win.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Alternative biological fuel sources returned again in 2004 with Team Nasamax's DM139-Judd.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2008, biofuels (10% ethanol for petrol engines and biodiesel for diesel engines) were allowed.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi was the first to use next-generation 10% BTL biodiesel developed by Shell and manufactured from biomass.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Beginning in 2009, new regulations allowed hybrid vehicles with either KERS or TERS (Kinetic/Thermal Energy Recovery System) setups.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, only electrical (i.e., battery) energy storage was allowed, ruling out flywheel-based energy recovery.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Cars with KERS were allowed to race in 2009 under specific classification rules.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2010, they have competed for points and the championship.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2012 the first KERS-equipped car won; the Audi R18 e-tron with a flywheel hybrid system by Williams Hybrid Power activated and drove the front wheels.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This was only allowed in certain zones after the car had accelerated to at least 120 km/h to cancel out the acceleration advantage that all-wheel-drive cars could gain out of corners.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In the same year, Toyota also started with a hybrid car, the TS030, which used KERS to power its rear wheels, meaning its usage was not restricted.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2025, the Automobile Club de l’Ouest is planning to introduce a hydrogen-electric prototype class.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This class will be a one-design class with a chassis provided by Red Bull Advanced Technologies-Oreca and a powertrain supplied by GreenGT.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The development of the hydrogen fuel cells powering the cars will be left to the teams themselves.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] According to the ACO's president Pierre Fillon, there is also a possibility of the cars being powered by a hydrogen combustion engine.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The performance of the class is expected to be competitive with the top Hypercar class.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Toyota unveiled new GR LH2 prototype for Gazoo Racing Europe.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With increased speeds around the track, brakes become a key issue for teams attempting to safely bring their cars down to a slow enough speed to make the Mulsanne Corner turn.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Disc brakes were first seen in 1953 when the Jaguar C-Type raced at Le Mans.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 1955 the Mercedes-Benz 300 SLR introduced the air brake using a large opening hood on the rear of the car.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Ford used a quick change brake rotor in 1966 to achieve their first victory at Le Mans.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In the 1980s, anti-lock braking systems became standard on most Group C cars as a safety measure, making it less likely that cars lose control at high speeds.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] By the late 1990s, reinforced carbon-carbon brakes were adopted for better stopping power.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Over the years, many manufacturers have managed to take the overall win, while even more have taken class wins.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The most successful marque in the history of the race is Porsche, which has taken nineteen overall victories, including seven in a row from 1981 to 1987 and 107 class victories.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi is next with thirteen wins, and Ferrari follows with eleven, also including six in a row from 1960 to 1965.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2000 Audi has dominated the event, winning 13 times in 15 years of participation.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi and Team Joest have had two hat-tricks, the first being in 2000, 2001, and 2002.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In contrast, Toyota won five races in a row and Bentley, Alfa Romeo, and Ford all won four races in a row, with Bentley recording two additional victories in other years.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2018, Toyota became only the second Japanese marque to win, following Mazda in 1991.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Mazda is also the only company to win with a rotary engine.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After Porsche's total of 107 class victories, Ferrari has 37, and Aston Martin, Audi, and Chevrolet each have 14.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Three drivers stand apart for their number of victories.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Initially, Jacky Ickx held the record at six, scoring victories between 1969 and 1982, earning him honorary citizenship to the town of Le Mans.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] His frequent racing partner, Derek Bell, trailing by a single win, with five.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, Tom Kristensen has beaten this record with nine wins between 1997 and 2013, including six in a row.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Three-time winner Woolf Barnato (1928 to 1930), Tazio Nuvolari (1933), Luis Fontés (1935), American racing legend A.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Foyt (1967), Nico Hülkenberg (2015), and Fernando Alonso (2018–2019) are the only drivers to have won every Le Mans in which they participated.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Henri Pescarolo won the race four times, and holds the record for the most Le Mans appearances at 33.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Japan's Yojiro Terada was active as a driver until 2008, and holds the record for the most Le Mans starts without an overall win.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Claude Ballot-Léna holds the most class victories other than Kristensen with seven wins in GT class cars between 1970 and 1986.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Graham Hill is the only driver to win the so-called *Triple Crown of Motorsport*, winning the Indianapolis 500 (1966), Monaco Grand Prix (1963, 1964, 1965, 1968, 1969), and the 24 Hours of Le Mans (1972).
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Le Mans has seen many fatal accidents due partly to the very high-speed nature of all variants of the track throughout history.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The largest one was in 1955 when at least 81 spectators (exact number unknown, many sources estimate 83) and driver Pierre Levegh were killed.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the wake of the disaster, many races were cancelled, including the Grand Prix races in Germany, Spain, France and Switzerland (the latter as a part of a blanket ban on motorsport round-track races that was maintained until 2022).
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The accident led to safety regulations in all motorsports for both driver and spectator protection.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Almost all decades in which Le Mans has been run have seen many horrific accidents, such as in 1972 when Jo Bonnier was catapulted into a forest surrounding the circuit after hitting a privately entered Ferrari near the Indianapolis section; Bonnier was killed instantly.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The 1980s was a decade where some of the race's worst-ever accidents occurred.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Although Armco barriers had been installed along the straight in 1969, there were still no chicanes on the Mulsanne Straight.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] It was here that almost all of the worst accidents occurred during that time.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1981, Belgian Thierry Boutsen crashed on the Mulsanne Straight in his WM-Peugeot, killing a marshal.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the same race, Frenchman Jean-Louis Lafosse was also killed on the Mulsanne Straight when his Rondeau suffered a suspension failure, steered very suddenly to the right, and slammed into the Armco barrier on the driver's side at extreme speeds.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The 1984 race saw British privateer John Sheldon crashing at more than 320 km/h (200 mph) at the Mulsanne Kink; his Aston Martin V8 powered Nimrod tore through the Armco barriers into the trees.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The resulting explosion was so violent that the woods next to the track caught fire.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Although Sheldon survived with severe burns, a track marshal was killed; two others were also severely injured.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Sheldon's teammate, American Drake Olson in the second Nimrod-Aston Martin, who was following him down the straight, crashed heavily after running over Sheldon's bodywork; he went into severe shock but survived with minor injuries.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The field was under the safety car for over an hour while the crash site was cleared, and the destroyed Armco barriers were replaced.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1985, a similar accident befell Briton Dudley Wood in a Porsche 962 during practice.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The impact of the car against the Armco, considering Wood was doing more than 370 km/h (230 mph), was so hard that it cracked the engine block.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1985, John Nielsen flipped his Sauber-Mercedes while going over the Mulsanne hump at more than 350 km/h (220 mph).
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The car landed on its roof and was destroyed, but Nielsen escaped without injury.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1986, Jo Gartner drove a Porsche 962C into the Mulsanne barriers and was killed instantly after the car rolled multiple times, vaulted some Armco barriers, and knocked down a telegraph pole.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Moreover, in 1987, American Price Cobb crashed a works Porsche 962C after slipping on oil during Wednesday practice.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The fuel tank exploded and the car burned to the ground, but Cobb escaped without injury.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Gartner's fatal accident remained the most recent death in the race until Allan Simonsen's crash in 2013.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] However, there was one fatality during a practice session in 1997 (Sebastien Enjolras).
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1999, the Mercedes-Benz CLRs suffered from aerodynamic instability leading to cars getting airborne and flipping backwards, no less than three times.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] After initially happening on Thursday to the #4 car, Mercedes rebuilt the chassis on Friday and claimed to have solved the problem, only for it to occur again at warmup on Saturday.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Mark Webber was the unlucky driver whose car flipped on both occasions.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The last and most damaging accident occurred during the race itself when Peter Dumbreck's CLR #5 became airborne, flying over the safety fencing and landing in the woods several metres away.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] No drivers were severely hurt in any of the three accidents.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] However, Mercedes-Benz withdrew its remaining entry and ended its entire sportscar programme to focus on F1 and the upcoming new DTM.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 2011, two horrific accidents occurred to two of the three factory Audis in the LMP1 class.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] 3 car driven by Allan McNish collided with one of the Ferrari GT cars, resulting in McNish's car smashing into the tyre wall and being thrown into the air at the Dunlop chicanes, resulting in pieces of bodywork flying over and nearly hitting many photographers on the other side of the barrier.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the eleventh hour of the race, another accident occurred to the No.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] 1 car driven by Mike Rockenfeller when he had contact with another Ferrari GT car.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the runup to Indianapolis corner, Rockenfeller's Audi was sent into the outside barrier at over 270 km/h (170 mph).
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Only the main cockpit safety cell of the car remained, along with major damage being done to the barriers that needed to be repaired before the race was resumed.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Audi had switched to a closed-cockpit car starting in 2011, a decision credited for the fact that neither driver was injured.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The 2014 regulations required all cars to be closed-cockpit due to the 2011 accident.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 2012, Anthony Davidson, driving for the returning Toyota team in a Toyota TS030 Hybrid, collided with a Ferrari 458 GT2 of Piergiuseppe Perazzini, and became airborne before crashing into the tyre barrier of the Mulsanne Corner at high speed.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The Ferrari also ended up in the barrier, flipping and coming to a halt on its roof.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 2013, Allan Simonsen died after crashing into the barriers at Tertre Rouge.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] When the car collided with the guard rail, a mature tree had been touching the barrier, thereby preventing the guard rail from performing its safety function.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Motors TV covered the Le Mans 24 Hours in its entirety in 2006 and 2007, including coverage of the scrutineering, qualifying, driver parade, warmup, and race.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the United States, FOX owned SPEED Channel, followed by Fox Sports 1 and Fox Sports 2 aired complete race coverage live either on-air or online through a combination of coverage from the French host broadcaster and its own pit reporting crew for several years.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] A United States television deal was not done for the 2018–19 WEC Super Season because of a renegotiation of its European contract.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 2008, Eurosport secured a multi-year deal to show the entire race, including the qualifying and the motorcycle race.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Every hour of the 2008 race was broadcast in segments on the main channel and Eurosport 2.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] However, a couple of hours were missed in recent years due to scheduling clashes with other sporting events.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In addition, Eurosport provided live streaming on its website to subscribers.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Since 2009, Eurosport and Eurosport 2 have covered all the action, and beginning in 2018, Eurosport gained United States broadcast rights for the World Endurance Championship for the race only on Motor Trend, a channel also owned by Eurosport's parent company.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Qualifying and practices aired on a direct-to-consumer streaming platform from Motor Trend magazine.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In Australia in 2012, Ten Sport showed the race live and in full online.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The race is also broadcast (in English) on the radio by Radio Le Mans.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Since 2001, the ACO has allowed the "Le Mans Legend" event to participate on the full Circuit de la Sarthe.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] These exhibition races involve classic cars that had previously run at Le Mans or are similar to those.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Each year, a particular era of cars may participate, with the featured era changing from year to year.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Though most drivers in this event are amateurs, some noted professional drivers have appeared to race cars they had previously run, such as Stirling Moss and Derek Bell.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Starting in 2002, the "Le Mans Classic" has been held as a biennial event on the full 13 km (8.1 mi) circuit in July.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The races take place over a full 24-hour day/night cycle, with starts on set times allowing cars from the same era to compete simultaneously.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] A team typically consists of a car in each class.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The team with the most points accumulated over five or six classes is declared the overall winner.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The classes are based on the era in which the cars would have competed.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The exact class requirements are re-evaluated for every event since the age for the youngest entries is shifted by two years for each event.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the first event, five classes ran more short races; later events have featured six classes running fewer but longer races.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Drivers are required to have an FIA International Competition license.
[src:bugatti-veyron/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] This event also includes a large Concours d'Elegance and auction.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi is located on an island in the Persian Gulf, off the Central West Coast.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Most of the city and the Emirate reside on the mainland connected to the rest of the country.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2023, Abu Dhabi's urban area had an estimated population of 2.5 million, out of 3.8 million in the emirate of Abu Dhabi.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Abu Dhabi Investment Authority (ADIA), headquartered in the city, is estimated to manage approximately US$1 trillion in assets, making it the world's third-largest sovereign wealth fund after Norway's Government Pension Fund Global and China's CIC.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi has over a trillion US dollars' worth of assets under management in a combination of sovereign wealth funds headquartered there.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi houses local and federal government offices and is the home of the United Arab Emirates Government and the Supreme Council for Financial and Economic Affairs.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The city is home to the UAE's president, a member of the Al Nahyan family.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi's rapid development and urbanisation, coupled with the massive oil and gas reserves and production and relatively high average income, have transformed it into a large, developed metropolis.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] It is the country's centre of politics and industry, and a major culture and commerce centre.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi accounts for about two-thirds of the roughly $503 billion UAE economy.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The area surrounding Abu Dhabi abounds in archaeological evidence from historical civilisations, such as the Umm Al Nar Culture, which dates back to the third millennium BC.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Other settlements were also found farther outside the modern city of Abu Dhabi, including the eastern and western regions of the Emirate.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] On December 2, 1971, Abu Dhabi, along with five other emirates, formed the United Arab Emirates (UAE).
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] This union was marked by the establishment of a federal government and the appointment of Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan as the first President of the UAE.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] "Abu" is Arabic for father, and "Dhabi" is the Arabic word for gazelle.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Bani Yas, the tribe from which the Al Nahyan family are drawn, was originally settled in the Liwa Oasis in the Emirate's western region.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] This tribe was the most significant in the area, having over 20 subsections.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In 1761, the discovery of fresh water by a hunting party led by Sheikh Dhiyab bin Isa Al Nahyan near the coast saw a settlement established there.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] A popular story is that the hunters were pursuing a gazelle, hence the name of the settlement.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Al Bu Falah subsection of the tribe were the first to establish the new settlement and remained the source of the tribal rulers.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Originally consisting of a fort and twenty houses, within two years the town consisted of a settlement of some 400 houses.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The fort remains at the centre of Abu Dhabi today, the Qasr Al Hosn.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The pearl diving business was a key industry prior to the discovery of oil reserves.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] According to a source about pearling, the Persian Gulf was the best location for pearls.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The pearl industry boomed from the late 19th century through to the second decade of the 20th century, however it is believed to date back around 7,000 years.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Pearl divers dive for one to three minutes and would have dived as many as thirty times per day.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Air tanks and any other sort of mechanical device were forbidden.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The divers had a leather nose clip and leather coverings on their fingers and big toes to protect them while they searched for oysters.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The divers were not paid for a day's work but received a portion of the season's earnings.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In the 19th century, as a result of treaties (known as "Truces" which gave the coast its name) entered into between Great Britain and the sheikhs of the Arab States of the Persian Gulf, Britain became the predominant influence in the area.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The main purpose of British interest was to protect the trade route to India from pirates, hence, the earlier name for the area, the "Pirate Coast".
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] After the suppression of piracy, other considerations came into play, such as a strategic need of the British to exclude other powers from the region.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Following their withdrawal from India in the year 1947, the British maintained their influence in Abu Dhabi as interest in the oil potential of the Persian Gulf grew.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In the mid to late 1930s, as the pearl trade declined, interest grew in the oil possibilities of the region.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] On 5 January 1936, Petroleum Development Trucial Coast Ltd (PDTC), an associate company of the Iraq Petroleum Company, entered into a concession agreement with the ruler, Sheikh Shakhbut bin Sultan Al Nahyan, to explore for oil.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] This was followed by a seventy-five-year concession signed in January 1939.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Owing to the desert terrain, inland exploration was fraught with difficulties.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In 1953, D'Arcy Exploration Company, the exploration arm of BP, obtained an offshore concession which was then transferred to a company created to operate the concession: Abu Dhabi Marine Areas (ADMA) was a joint venture between BP and Compagnie Française des Pétroles (later Total).
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In 1958, using a marine drilling platform, the ADMA Enterprise, oil was discovered in the Umm Shaif field at a depth of about 2,669 metres (8,755 ft).
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] This was followed in 1959 by PDTC's onshore discovery well at Murban No.3.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] ADMA discovered the Bu Hasa oil field in 1962 and the Lower Zakum oil field in 1963.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Today, in addition to the oil fields mentioned, the main producing fields onshore are Asab, Sahil and Shah, and offshore are al-Bunduq, and Abu al-Bukhoosh.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Perceived mismanagement of the emirate's oil revenues, as well as fears of a pan-Arab uprising, led to the British backing a bloodless coup by Shakhbut's younger brother Zayed Al Nahyan on August 6, 1966.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The city of Abu Dhabi is on the southeastern side of the Arabian Peninsula, adjoining the Persian Gulf.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] It is on an island less than 250 metres (820 ft) from the mainland and is joined to the mainland by the Maqta and Mussafah Bridges.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] A third, Sheikh Zayed Bridge, designed by Zaha Hadid, opened in late 2010.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi Island is also connected to Saadiyat Island by a five-lane motorway bridge.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Al-Mafraq bridge connects the city to Reem Island and was completed in early 2011.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] This is a multi-layer interchange bridge and it has 27 lanes which allow roughly 25,000 automobiles to move per hour.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] There are three major bridges in the project, the largest has eight lanes, four leaving Abu Dhabi city and four coming in.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Most of Abu Dhabi city is located on the island itself, but it has many suburban districts on the mainland, for example, Khalifa City A, B, and C; Khalifa City Al Raha Beach; Al Bahia City A, B, and C; Al Shahama; Al Rahba; Between Two Bridges; Baniyas; Shamkha; Al Wathba and Mussafah Residential.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Gulf waters of Abu Dhabi holds the world's largest population of Indo-Pacific humpbacked dolphins.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] To the east of the island is the Mangrove National Park, located on Al Qurm Corniche.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] *Al-Qurm* (ٱلْقُرْم) is Arabic for "The Mangrove".
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi has a hot desert climate (Köppen climate classification *BWh*).
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Sunny blue skies can be expected throughout the year.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The months of May to September are generally extremely hot and humid.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The peak summer months are July and August, with maximum temperatures averaging above 40 °C (104 °F).
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] During this time, sandstorms occur intermittently, in some cases reducing visibility to a few metres.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Due to high humidity, especially in coastal areas, the heat index, or "feels-like" temperature, can be significantly higher than the actual air temperature.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Dust storms are common during the hot, dry months, affecting air quality and visibility.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The cooler season is from November to March, which ranges between moderately hot to mild.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] This period also sees dense fog on some days and a few days of rain.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] On average, January is the coolest month of the year.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Since the Tropic of Cancer passes through the emirate, the southern part falls within the Tropics.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Despite the coolest month having an 18.8 °C (65.8 °F) average, its climate is far too dry to be classed as tropical.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi City is the capital of the Emirate of Abu Dhabi, and the local government of Abu Dhabi is directly led by the Ruler of Abu Dhabi.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi is the largest, and wealthiest of the seven emirates, and it plays a crucial role in the UAE's governance and economy.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Ruler has the executive authority to issue local laws, create or merge government departments, and appoint heads of departments.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Ruler of Abu Dhabi appoints the Abu Dhabi Executive Council to lead the day-to-day management of government affairs.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Department of Municipal Affairs is responsible for municipal affairs for the entire emirate.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi is part of the Central Capital District, which is separate from the eastern and western municipal regions of the Emirate of Abu Dhabi.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The main settlement of the eastern region, officially "Al Ain Region" since a decree by Sheikh Khalifa in March 2017, is Al Ain City, and that of the western region, officially "Al Dhafra Region" as per the same decree, is Madinat Zayed.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Government of the Emirate of Abu Dhabi officially leads both the city and greater emirate with agencies operating out of Abu Dhabi with branches in other cities.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Abu Dhabi Government has agencies and organisations operating across the emirate such as the Abu Dhabi Urban Planning Council and the Regulation and Supervision Bureau, which are responsible for infrastructure projects in the city.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Because Abu Dhabi is the capital of the UAE, it also serves as the headquarters of the Federal government of the United Arab Emirates, the office of the President of the United Arab Emirates, and seat of the Federal Supreme Council.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Abu Dhabi Government Media Office (ADGMO) was formed in 2019 and is responsible for representing the government in the media, organising press conferences for the emirate and monitoring local and international media.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] It is a state-sponsored organisation that communicates the latest developments in the capital, and the emirate's vision, values and traditions.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The city was planned under the guidance of Sheikh Zayed by Japanese architect Katsuhiko Takahashi in 1967 initially for a population of 40,000.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The density of Abu Dhabi varies, with high employment density in the central area, high residential densities in central downtown and lower densities in the suburban districts.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In the dense areas, most of the concentration is achieved with medium- and high-rise buildings.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Other notable modern buildings include the Aldar Headquarters, the first circular skyscraper in the Middle East and the Emirates Palace with its design inspired by Arab heritage.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi already has a number of supertall skyscrapers under construction throughout the city.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Some of the tallest buildings on the skyline include the 382 m (1,253.28 ft) Central Market Residential Tower, the 324 m (1,062.99 ft) The Landmark and the 74-story, 310 m (1,017.06 ft) Sky Tower, all of them completed.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Many other skyscrapers over 150 m (492.13 ft) (500 ft) are either proposed or approved and could transform the city's skyline.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] As of July 2008, there were 62 high-rise buildings 23 to 150 m (75.46 to 492.13 ft) under construction, approved for construction, or proposed for construction.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Sheikh Zayed Grand Mosque represents a key fixture of the city's architectural patrimony.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Its construction was initiated under the administration of the late President Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan, a key figure in the foundation of the modern United Arab Emirates.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The mosque was constructed with materials from countries around the world, including Italy, Germany, Morocco, Pakistan, India, Turkey, Iran, China, the United Kingdom, New Zealand, Greece, and the United Arab Emirates.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] More than 3,000 workers and 38 contracting companies took part in the construction of the mosque.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Consideration of durability motivated the choice of many materials specified in the design of the structure.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] These materials include marble, stone, gold, semi-precious stones, crystals, and ceramics.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The building is large enough to safely contain a maximum of approximately 41,000 people.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The overall structure is 22,412 square metres (241,240 square feet).
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The internal prayer halls were initially opened in December 2007.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] As one of the most visited buildings in the UAE, the Sheikh Zayed Grand Mosque Center was established to manage the day-to-day operations, as a place of worship and Friday gathering and as a centre of learning and discovery through its education and visitor programs.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In July 2019, the Grand Mosque was listed among the top global attractions by TripAdvisor.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] As a part of its Travelers Choice Awards, the travel website placed the architectural masterpiece on number three out of the 750 landmarks considered from 68 countries.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In May 2021, the Sheikh Zayed Grand Mosque Center attended the Arabian Travel Market 2021 exhibition.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] This was part of the centre's core strategy to be active in the religious and cultural aspects of society.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Founder's Memorial, a monument and visitor centre in Abu Dhabi, United Arab Emirates (UAE) is a memorial to Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan, the first President of the United Arab Emirates, who died in 2004.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The memorial consists of an open Heritage Garden and Sanctuary Garden at the centre of which is a cubic pavilion housing The Constellation, an artwork dedicated to Zayed's memory.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The UAE Presidential Palace, *Qaṣr Al-Waṭan* ("Palace of the Nation"), opened to the public in March 2019.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] It was built on the grounds of Ladies beach and construction was finished in 2018.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Historically, 'barza' refers to a majlis session during which important matters can be brought to the attention of a Sheikh.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] After the Great Hall, it is the largest space in the UAE's Presidential Palace which holds up to 300 guests.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Abrahamic Family House, a multi-faith complex on Saadiyat Island, includes the Imam Al-Tayeb Mosque, St.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Francis Church, and the Moses Ben Maimon Synagogue, the UAE's first purpose-built synagogue.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The project was inaugurated on 16 February 2023 and officially opened to the public on 1 March 2023.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] On 22 September 2019, the Department of Community Development (DCD) in Abu Dhabi held a ceremony to grant licenses to 17 churches and the first-ever traditional Hindu temple.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The listed churches were Catholic, Orthodox and Protestant churches, including St Joseph's Cathedral.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The initiative was taken under the slogan "A Call for Harmony", to allow people from all religions and cultures to practice their faith in the country.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Qasr Al Hosn is the oldest building in the Emirate of Abu Dhabi, built by the Bani Yas tribe in 1761.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] It was once the seat of the government and the palace of the ruling Al Nahyan family.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Today, it is a museum open to all visitors portraying the history of Abu Dhabi and early lifestyles.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] It is where the visitors will notice the art Talli, a traditional form of decorative embroidery done by women, and the making of Al Sadu patterns which represent symbols of daily life.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] A three-screen mini-theatre is available which describes the traditional form of weaving practised by Bedouin women.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi has several parks, gardens, a zoo, and more than 400 kilometres (249 miles) of coastline, of which 10 kilometres (6 miles) are public beaches.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The UAE's large hydrocarbon wealth gives it one of the highest GDP per capita in the world and Abu Dhabi owns the majority of these resources 95% of the oil and 92% of gas.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi thus holds 9% of the world's proven oil reserves (98.2bn barrels) and almost 5% of the world's natural gas (5.8 billion cubic metres or 200 billion cubic feet).
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] As of April 2022, oil production in the UAE was about 3.0 million barrels per day (BPD).
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The UAE is looking to expand its maximum production capacity from approximately 4 million BPD to 5 million BPD by 2030.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In recent years, the focus has turned to gas as increasing domestic consumption for power, desalination and reinjection of gas into oil fields increases demand.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Gas extraction is not without its difficulties, however, as demonstrated by the sour gas project at Shah where the gas is rich in hydrogen sulfide content and expensive to develop and process.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2009, the government diversified its economic plans.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Served by high oil prices, the country's non-oil and gas GDP outstripped that attributable to the energy sector.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Non-oil and gas GDP now constitutes 64% of the UAE's total GDP.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] This trend is reflected in Abu Dhabi with substantial new investment in industry, real estate, tourism and retail.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] As Abu Dhabi is the largest oil producer of the UAE, it has reaped the most benefits from this trend.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] It has taken on an active diversification and liberalisation program to reduce the UAE's reliance on the hydrocarbon sector.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] This is evident in the emphasis on industrial diversification with the completion of free zones, Industrial City of Abu Dhabi, twofour54 Abu Dhabi media free zone and the construction of another, ICAD II, in the pipeline.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] There has also been a drive to promote tourism and real estate with the Abu Dhabi Tourism Authority and the Tourism and Development Investment Company undertaking several large-scale development projects.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] These will be served by improved transport infrastructure, with a new port, an expanded airport and a proposed rail link between Abu Dhabi and Dubai all in the development stages.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi's Emirate is the wealthiest of the UAE in terms of Gross domestic product (GDP) and per capita income.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] More than $1 trillion is invested worldwide in the city.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2010, the GDP per capita reached $49,600, which ranks ninth in the world.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Taxation in Abu Dhabi, as in the rest of the UAE, is nil for a resident or a non-bank, non-oil company.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi is also planning many future projects sharing with the Cooperation Council for the Arab States of the Gulf (GCC) and taking 29% of all the GCC future plannings.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The UAE has a fast-growing economy: in 2006 the per capita income grew by 9%, providing a GDP per capita of $49,700 and ranking third in the world at purchasing power parity.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi's government is looking to expand revenue from oil and gas production to tourism and other things that would attract different types of people.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] This goal is seen in the amount of attention Abu Dhabi is giving its International Airport.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The airport experienced a 30%+ growth in passenger usage in 2009.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] This idea of diversifying the economy is also seen in the Abu Dhabi Economic Vision 2030 planned by the Abu Dhabi Urban Planning Council.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In this plan, Abu Dhabi's economy will be sustainable and not dependent on any single source of revenue.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] More specifically the non-oil portion of income is planned to be increased from about 40% to about 70%.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] As of July 2019, Abu Dhabi allocated $163 million to finance global entertainment partners as part of its plan to diversify the economy and wean it off oil.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Many Hollywood and other national film production teams have used parts of the UAE as filming locations.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Neighbouring Dubai gets a lot of attention, but in recent years Abu Dhabi has become a popular destination.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Etihad Towers and Emirates Palace Hotel were some of the city's landmarks used as filming locations for the movie *Furious 7*, in which cars rush through the building and smashed through the windows of the towers.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2018, Abu Dhabi launched Ghadan 21, a string of initiatives to diversify the economy.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] There are four main areas these initiatives must fall under: business and investment, society, knowledge and innovation, and lifestyle.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The first phase includes over 50 initiatives that reflect the priorities of citizens, residents and investors.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The desalinated water supply and power production are managed by the Abu Dhabi Water and Electricity Authority (ADWEA).
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] As of 2006, it supplied 560.2 MiGD (million imperial gallons per day) of water, while the water demand for 2005–06 was estimated to be 511 MiGD.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Environment Agency of Abu Dhabi (EAD) states that groundwater is the most significant source of water, as well as desalinated potable water, and treated sewage effluent.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] At 40.6 MiGD, the Umm Al Nar storage is the largest water source for Abu Dhabi, followed by the rivers Shuweihat and Taweelah.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] With falling groundwater level and rising population density, Abu Dhabi faces a severely acute water shortage.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] On average each Abu Dhabi resident uses 550 litres (120 imp gal; 150 US gal) of water per day.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi daily produces 1,532 tonnes of solid wastes which are dumped at three landfill sites by the Abu Dhabi Municipality.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The daily domestic wastewater production is 330 MiGD and industrial waste water is 40 MiGD.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] A large portion of the sewerage flows as waste into streams and separation plants.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The city's per capita electricity consumption is about 41,000 kWh and the total supplied is 8,367 MW as of 2007.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The distribution of electricity is carried out by companies run by SCIPCO Power and APC Energy.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] As part of UAE's Energy Strategy 2050 to reduce the carbon emission of power generation by 70%, Noor Abu Dhabi solar park project which is the largest solar project in the world was completed on 2 July 2019.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Abu Dhabi Fire Service runs 13 fire stations that attend about 2,000 fire and rescue calls per year.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] State-owned Etisalat and private du communication companies provide telephone and cell phone service to the city.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Cellular coverage is extensive, and both GSM and CDMA (from Etisalat and Du) services are available.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Etisalat, the government-owned telecommunications provider, held a virtual monopoly over telecommunication services in Abu Dhabi prior to the establishment of other, smaller telecommunications companies such as Emirates Integrated Telecommunications Company (EITC – better known as Du) in 2006.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Internet was introduced into Abu Dhabi in 1995.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The current network is supported by a bandwidth of 6 GB, with 50,000 dialup and 150,000 broadband ports.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Etisalat announced implementing a fiber-to-the-home (FTTH) network in Abu Dhabi during the third quarter of 2009 to make the emirate the world's first city to have such a network.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi in the 1960s and 70s was planned for a predicted topmost population of 600,000.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Following the urban planning ideals of the time period, the city has high-density tower blocks and wide grid-pattern roads.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The population density is at its apex on the most northerly part of the island.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] At this point, the main streets have a large amount of 20- to 30-story towers.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] These towers are in a rectangular pattern, and inside is an ordinary grid pattern of roads with low rise buildings such as 2-story villas or 6-story low-rise buildings.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Due to this planning, a modern city with tall offices, apartment buildings, broad boulevards, and busy shops is present.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Principal thoroughfares are the Corniche, Airport Road, Sheikh Zayed Street, Hamdan Street, and Khalifa Street.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi is known in the region for its greenery; the former desert strip today includes numerous parks and gardens.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The design of the inner city roads and main roads are quite organised.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Starting from the Corniche, all horizontal streets are oddly numbered, while all vertical streets are evenly numbered.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Mail is generally delivered to post-office boxes only; however, there is door-to-door delivery for commercial organisations.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] There are many parks throughout the city.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Entrance is usually free for children, however, there is often an entrance fee for adults.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Corniche, the city's seaside promenade, is about 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) in length, with gardens, playgrounds, and a BMX/skateboard ring.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2007, the Abu Dhabi Urban Planning Council (UPC) was established, which is the agency responsible for the future of Abu Dhabi's urban environments and the expert authority behind the visionary Plan Abu Dhabi 2030 Urban Structure Framework Plan that was published in September 2007.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The UPC is also working on similar plans for the regions of Al-Ain and Al-Gharbia.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Human rights organisations have heavily criticised violations of human rights in Abu Dhabi.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] As with other parts of the UAE, foreign workers are not given proper treatment and many companies (both government and private) have yet to improve working conditions.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2025, Abu Dhabi was ranked as the safest city in the world for the ninth year running by the statistical analysis website Numbeo.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi ranks as the 67th most expensive city in the world and the second-most in the region behind Dubai.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] As of 2014, 477,000 of 2,650,000 people living in the emirate were UAE nationals.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Approximately 80% of the population were expatriates.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The median age in the emirate was about 30.1 years.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The crude birth rate, as of 2005, was 13.6%, while the crude death rate was about 2%.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Article 7 of the UAE's Provisional Constitution declares Islam the official state religion of the UAE.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The majority of the inhabitants of Abu Dhabi are migrants from Nepal, India, Pakistan, Russia, Ethiopia, Somalia, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, the Philippines, China, Uganda, Vietnam, the United Kingdom, France, Italy, Tanzania and various countries from across the Arab world.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Some of these expatriates have been in the country for decades with only a few of them awarded citizenship.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Consequently, English, Hindi-Urdu (Hindustani), Malayalam, Tamil, Telugu, Gujarati, Marathi, Tulu, Somali, Tigrinya, Amharic and Bengali are widely spoken.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The native-born population are Arabic-speaking Arabs who are part of a clan-based society.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Al Nahyan family, part of the al-Falah branch of the Bani Yas clan, rules the emirate and has a central place in society.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] There are also Arabs who are from other parts of the Arab world.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Rapidly developing transportation in Abu Dhabi city is anchored by vast systems of highways connecting various islands and suburbs together alongside expanding public and private transport options.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The main Abu Dhabi island is connected by three vast highways with their own bridges, the oldest of which is Al Maqta Bridge, built in 1968 as the first connection to the previously small fishing village on the island, now part of the E22 highway.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] As the city expands, new bridges and roads have been constructed, or are currently under construction to link the main island with Al Maryah Island, Al Reem Island, Saadiyat Island, and other previously undeveloped islands.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] For example, in 2023, Sheikh Khaled bin Mohamed Al Nahyan inaugurated the Umm Yifeenah Bridge, an 11 km highway connection between Al Reem Island and Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Street.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] This change, and many other, are a part of Abu Dhabi's 2030 Urban Structure Framework Plan.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Zayed International Airport (AUH) is the city's main aviation hub and the second busiest airport in the UAE.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Passenger numbers at Zayed International Airport rose by 17.2 percent in 2015, with more than 23 million travelers passing through its terminals during that year.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] A second runway and new terminal was also built recently.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In July 2024, it was reported that the airport launched the world's first-of-its-kind "Smart Travel" biometric.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] On 30 June 2019, the Department of Community Development (DCD) in Abu Dhabi officially inaugurated a multi-faith prayer room at Zayed International Airport.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Located away from the main airport, the prayer room aims at enhancing the country's "position as an international hub for tolerance".
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi City is additionally served by the Al Bateen Executive Airport, situated on the main Abu Dhabi island, which was the old international airport for Abu Dhabi until AUH opened in 1982.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The airport underwent renovation and expansion in 2022 to accommodate twin-aisle jets and resumed operation to private, business, and VIP traffic in addition to hosting an Abu Dhabi Police search and rescue base.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] On December 5, 2024, Zayed International Airport in Abu Dhabi (AUH) won the title of "World's Most Beautiful Airport" at the Prix Versailles, a prestigious award for architecture and design.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The award recognised its impressive architectural design in the Airports category.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi City is connected to the second phase of the Etihad Rail network, completed in 2023, for freight operations across the seven emirates.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Passenger traffic has been confirmed and will allow for travel from Abu Dhabi city to other emirates on the network, however no date on commencement of operation has been set.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Public transport systems in Abu Dhabi include public buses, taxis, ferries, and hydroplanes.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] A massive expansion of public transport is anticipated within the framework of the government's Surface Transport Master Plan 2030.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The expansion was expected to see 130 km (81 mi) of metro and 340 km (210 mi) of tramways and bus rapid transit (BRT) routes.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The city has nonetheless planned for further smart public transport options in various areas within the city, such as Yas Island and Saadiyat Island, in addition to expected rail service to other nearby cities.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The first town bus entered service in about 1969 but this was all part of a very informal service.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] There are other inter-city buses departing the Abu Dhabi central bus station; these inter-city buses are not only intra-emirate buses, but also inter-emirate services.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] On 30 June 2008, the Department of Transport began public bus service in Abu Dhabi with four routes.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] There are also public buses serving the airport.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In an attempt to entice people to use the bus system, all routes were zero-fare until the end of 2008.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The four routes, which operate between 6 am and midnight every day, run at a frequency of 10 to 20 minutes.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Within the first week of service, the bus network had seen high usage.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Some of the buses, which have a maximum capacity of 45 passengers, only had room for standing left.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Some bus drivers reported as many as 100 passengers on a bus at one time.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Due to the new, zero-fare bus service success, many taxi drivers were losing business.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Taxi drivers have seen a considerable decrease in the demand for taxis while lines were forming for the buses.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] As of 2021, the Abu Dhabi public bus system had completed 53.3 million passenger trips, with a fleet of 583 buses for the city of Abu Dhabi.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2022, Abu Dhabi launched autonomous self-driving public transport options in Yas Island and Saadiyat Island.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The route in Saadiyat Island stops at cultural and tourist stops such as Louvre Abu Dhabi, NYU Abu Dhabi, and Sorbonne University Abu Dhabi whereas the Yas Island route focuses on the attractions in the island such as Ferrari World Abu Dhabi.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The expansion include autonomous trams (Automated Rapid Transit or "ART"), taxis, and minibuses.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] During October 2023, the Integrated Transport Centre (ITC) launched the ART Service on mainland Abu Dhabi as a pilot phase as part of the Smart Mobility project.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] It spans approximately 27 kilometres from Reem Mall, Al Reem Island, until Marina Mall, serving 25 stations in total.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2025, WeRide and Uber announced the launch of Level 4 fully driverless Robotaxi commercial operations.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Public commercial operations commenced on 26 November without a vehicle specialist inside the AV, starting with Yas Island.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] This initiative is supported by Abu Dhabi's Integrated Transport Centre.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The others are Musaffah Port and Khalifa Port, which opened in 2012.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] They are owned by Abu Dhabi Ports Company and managed by Abu Dhabi Terminals.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Water transport includes water taxis which can accommodate up to 12 passengers, and ferries which can carry up to 100 passengers on board.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Water taxis can be hired for point-to-point travel across the city's waterways, offering a convenient option for shorter trips, and ferry transport system is a convenient and scenic way to travel between the city's islands and mainland.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2021, the number of passengers who used public ferries reached 114,093.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi introduced four toll gates in 2021 on all bridges (Sheikh Zayed Bridge, Maqtaa Bridge, Mussafah Bridge, and Sheikh Khalifa Bridge) entering the main Abu Dhabi island that only operate during peak hours, and by year-end had over 1.8 million registered cars in the system.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Drivers must manually create an account to add balance to their toll gate allowance.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi's toll gate system, known as **Darb**, is aimed at reducing traffic congestion and promoting smoother traffic flow.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Drivers must register their vehicles on the **Darb app** or the official website.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The system automatically deducts the toll charges from a prepaid account.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi's first flying taxi vertiport will open at the Zayed Port Cruise Terminal by late 2025.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] It will serve helicopters and eVTOLs, offering direct access to Saadiyat Island, the Corniche, and the Louvre Abu Dhabi.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi has a diverse and multicultural society.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The city's cultural imprint as a small, ethnically homogeneous pearling community was changed with the arrival of other ethnic groups and nationals—first by the Iranians in the early 1900s, and later by various African, Asian, European, and Middle Eastern ethnicities in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi has been criticised for perpetuating a class-based society, where migrant workers are in the lower classes, and suffer abuse which "is endemic to the system".
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Major holidays in Abu Dhabi include *Eid al Fitr* which marks the end of *Ramadan*, Eid ul-Adha which marks the end of Hajj, and National Day (2 December) which marks the formation of the United Arab Emirates.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] This unique socioeconomic development in the Persian Gulf has meant that Abu Dhabi is generally more tolerant than its neighbours, including Saudi Arabia.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Emiratis have been known for their tolerance; Christian churches, Hindu temples, Sikh gurdwaras (with the first synagogue commencing construction in 2020), and Buddhist temples can be found alongside mosques.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The cosmopolitan atmosphere is gradually growing; as a result, there are a variety of African, Asian, European, Middle Eastern, and Western schools, cultural centres, and themed restaurants.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi is home to several cultural institutions, including the Cultural Foundation and the National Theater.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Cultural Foundation, while closed for reconstruction as of spring 2011, is home to the UAE Public Library and Cultural Center.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Various cultural societies such as the Abu Dhabi Classical Music Society have a strong and visible following in the city.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The recently launched Emirates Foundation offers grants in support of the arts and to advance science and technology, education, environmental protection, and social development.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The International Prize for Arabic Fiction (IPAF) will be based in Abu Dhabi.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The city also stages hundreds of conferences and exhibitions each year in its state-of-the-art venues, including the Abu Dhabi National Exhibition Centre (ADNEC), which is the Persian Gulf's largest exhibition centre and welcomes around 1.8 million visitors every year.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The Red Bull Air Race World Series has been a spectacular sporting staple for the city for many years, bringing tens of thousands to the waterfront.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Another major event is the Abu Dhabi International Petroleum Exhibition and Conference (ADIPEC).
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The diversity of cuisine in Abu Dhabi reflects the cosmopolitan nature of society.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Arab food is trendy and is available everywhere in the city, from the small shawarma to the upscale restaurants in the city's many hotels.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Fast food and South Asian cuisine are also trendy and are widely available.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The sale and consumption of pork, though not illegal, is regulated and sold only to non-Muslims in designated areas.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Similarly, the sale of alcoholic beverages is regulated.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] A liquor permit is required to purchase alcohol; however, alcohol is available in bars and restaurants within four or five stars hotels.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] *Shisha* and *qahwa* boutiques are also popular in Abu Dhabi.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Poetry in Abu Dhabi and the UAE is highly regarded and often centres around satire, religion, family, chivalry, and love.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] According to an article from an Abu Dhabi tourism page, sheikhs, teachers, sailors, and princes make up a large bulk of the poets within the UAE. al-Khalil ibn Ahmad al-Farahidi formed a unique form of poetry to the UAE in the 8th century and was written in 16 metre.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Another Emirati poet, Ibn Daher, is from the 17th century.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Daher is important because he used Nabati poetry (AKA Bedouin poetry), a type of poetry written in the vernacular instead of classical/religious Arabic.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Other important poets from the UAE are Mubarak Al Oqaili (1880–1954), Salem bin Ali al Owais (1887–1959), and Abdulla bin Sulayem (1905–1976).
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] These poets made headway in Classical Arabic poetry as opposed to the Nabati poetry of the 17th century.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Today in Abu Dhabi, a group called the Abu Dhabi Cultural Foundation works to preserve the art and culture of the city.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] According to an article from the English Pen Atlas, Al Jawaher wal la'li was the first manuscript to come out of the UAE.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] According to another article, this book was written in the 1990s and was banned in the city for some time for making accusations about the ruling family.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] For cultural influences, Abu Dhabi, since 2010, has become one of the major shooting spots for many film companies, including Hollywood.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2024, the Madison Square Garden Company confirmed that a second Sphere venue, identical to the Sphere in Las Vegas would be built in Abu Dhabi.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The following year in 2025 it was confirmed that Disney would build a theme-park in Abu Dhabi called Disneyland Abu Dhabi.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi is home to international and local private schools and universities, including government-sponsored INSEAD, New York University Abu Dhabi, Khalifa University, Higher Colleges of Technology, Sorbonne University Abu Dhabi, and Abu Dhabi University.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] New York University opened a government-sponsored satellite campus in Abu Dhabi in September 2010.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] All schools in the emirate are under the authority of the Abu Dhabi Education Council.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] This organisation oversees and administers public schools and licenses and inspects private schools.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] From 2009, the council has brought over thousands of licensed teachers from native English speaking countries to support their New School Model Program in government schools.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Every year in the season of admissions, an exhibition is launched in Abu Dhabi Exhibition Center under government supervision.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Universities from every corner of the world exhibit their career programs and scholarship programs.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] Heriot-Watt University, University of Bolton, Cambridge University, Oxford University, the Petroleum Institute, Khalifa University, and Abu Dhabi University attend.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] In October 2019, Abu Dhabi announced the world's first graduate-level AI research institution, Mohamed bin Zayed University of Artificial Intelligence (MBZUAI).
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] It enables graduation for students, businesses and governments to advance artificial intelligence.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p01] The university began accepting applications for masters and PhD programmes a year before the classes, which are scheduled to begin in September 2020.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] Abu Dhabi has a diverse and expanding sporting culture underpinned by investments in sporting infrastructure and the hosting of global sporting events.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] Liwa Motorsport and traditional sports such as camel racing and equestrian sports have developed alongside popular modern sports such as Jiu-jitsu and football.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] Abu Dhabi follows the UAE's National Sport Strategy 2031 which aims to increase general participation in sports and expand the types and frequency of sport facilities available in the city.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] Zayed Sport City (ZSC) is a large free zone complex in the heart of Abu Dhabi city with a mixed-use of properties and sporting facilities to encourage sport participation.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] ZSC offers practice facilities for basketball, billiards, football, paintball, and a dedicated ice rink.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] The complex is also home to the Zayed Sports City Stadium, the largest in the UAE with a seating capacity of 45,000 and is the headquarters of the Abu Dhabi Sports Council, which is responsible for hosting events in the city and Mubadala Arena, the home of the UAE Jiu Jitsu team.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] Jiu Jitsu is a popular sport in the city with a dedicated complex in the Mubadala Arena.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] It is a 'Soft Art' originated from the ancient martial art of the Samurai in Japan several centuries ago and it has been adopted by Brazil in the early 1900s.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] Jiu Jitsu does not include punches or kicks, but it applies the techniques such as throws, control positions and locks.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] Abu Dhabi government's Abu Dhabi Education Council (ADEC) maintains a comprehensive after-school program for interested and talented jiujitsu students.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] The Abu Dhabi Jiujitsu Schools Program began in 2008 under the patronage of crown prince (now President) Mohammed bin Zayed Al Nahyan, a keen Brazilian jiu-jitsu competitor.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] The program launched in 14 schools for pupils in grades 6 and 7 and has since expanded to 42 government schools, with 81 Brazilian coaches brought in as instructors.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] 9 to 13-year-old students are taught Brazilian jiu-jitsu as part of the curriculum.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] The plan is for up to 500 schools to be participating in the school-Jitsu program by 2015.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] The project was set up by special request of Sheikh Mohammad bin Zayed Al Nahyan to the head coach of the Emirates jiu-jitsu team, Carlos "Carlão" Santos, now also the managing director of the School-Jitsu Project.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] Football is the most popular sport in the city and the city has four football stadiums, namely Al Jazeera Stadium, Al Wahda Stadium, Sheikh Zayed Football Stadium (Zayed Sports City) and Hazza Stadium.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] The city hosts the Al Jazira Club, Al Wahda FC, and Baniyas Club, all of which compete at the UAE Pro League.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] In addition to local tournaments, the city has hosted international football events including five FIFA Club World Cup and the 2019 AFC Asian Cup.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] The city hosts the Abu Dhabi Grand Prix of Formula One, which has been held at the Yas Marina Circuit since 2009.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] The race takes place late in the Formula One season in November or December, and it is usually the last race of the season.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] The Yas Marina Circuit is one of the most expensive racing tracks built and regularly hosts various other local races and tours.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] The circuit has also hosted other events such as the V8 Supercars series of Dubai.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] Abu Dhabi regularly hosts the International Judo Federation Abu Dhabi grand slam.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] Engendering some criticism, the International Judo Federation refused to allow the Israeli flag and the Israeli national anthem at the international games in 2017.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] Some referred to this action as anti-Semitic.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] The ban on Israeli symbols was lifted in 2018 and Israeli flag and the national anthem was allowed to be displayed.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] Israeli minister of sports Miri Regev was also allowed to attend the event.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] In March 2019, Abu Dhabi hosted the first Special Olympics World Games in the Middle East.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] The event took place from 14 to 21 March 2019 and featured more than 7,500 athletes participating in 24 sporting disciplines.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] The official World Games Flame of Hope was lit in Athens and flown to Abu Dhabi, where it then embarked on the torch run, visiting all seven emirates of the UAE.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] It was the first time the Special Olympics World Games were hosted in the Middle East and North Africa region, with Abu Dhabi being the host city.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] More than 2,500 coaches and 20,000+ volunteers were available in the Olympics.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] The city has hosted multiple international cricket tournaments, such as the ICC Men's T20 World Cup, and tennis events such as the Mubadala World Tennis Championship.It has also hosted many UFC events.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] World Abu Dhabi, SeaWorld Abu Dhabi and Jubail Mangrove Park.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] On 29 April 2022, Abu Dhabi announced a 100% capacity for commercial activities, tourist attractions and events in the emirate.
[src:bugatti-veyron/abu-dhabi-p02] The Walt Disney Company announced on 7 May 2025 that it plans to build its seventh worldwide theme park resort in Abu Dhabi on Yas Island.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] Born in Galliate, province of Novara (Piedmont), Achille Varzi was the son of a textile manufacturer.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] As a young man, he was a successful motorcycle racer of Garelli, DOT, Moto Guzzi and Sunbeam, and rode seven times in the Isle of Man TT from 1924 before switching to auto racing in 1928 where, for the next ten years, he would rival Tazio Nuvolari, Rudolf Caracciola and Bernd Rosemeyer.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] Varzi's first race car was a Type 35 Bugatti but he shortly changed to driving an Alfa Romeo, a brand with which he would score many victories during the 1929 Italian racing season.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] In 1930 Varzi acquired a vehicle from the relatively new Maserati company.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] He drove it as well as an Alfa Romeo earning his country's racing championship, a feat he would repeat in 1934.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] One of his big victories came at the prestigious Targa Florio where he upset the favored Louis Chiron.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] Following his win at the 1933 Tripoli Grand Prix, a race at the time associated with a lottery, Varzi was at the forefront of allegations that the race had been fixed.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] Varzi won six Grand Prix in 1934 driving the Alfa Romeo P3, at Alessandria, Tripoli, Targa Florio, Penya Rhin at Barcelona, Coppa Ciano and Nice.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] Although the Alfa Romeo team had proved to be competitive under the management of Enzo Ferrari, Varzi decided to join the Auto Union team, racing for them between 1935 and 1937.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] This move coincided with Varzi having serious personal problems, including an addiction to morphine and a difficult affair with Ilse Pietsch (Engel/Hubitsch/Feininger), the wife of fellow driver Paul Pietsch.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] Quickly overshadowed by teammate Bernd Rosemeyer, his trips to the winners circle dropped to only four, but he did win his third Tripoli Grand Prix in his third different vehicle.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] By 1938 he had dropped out of sight and the advent of World War II ended racing in Europe.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] During the war, Varzi overcame his drug addiction and settled down with his new wife, Norma Colombo.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] At the end of the War, Varzi made a remarkable comeback at the age of 42.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] In 1946 he attempted to race a Maserati for the Indianapolis 500 but failed to qualify.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] In 1947, he won three minor Grand Prix races and traveled to Argentina to race in the Buenos Aires Grand Prix.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] During practice runs for the 1948 Swiss Grand Prix, a light rain fell on the Bremgarten track in Berne, Switzerland.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] Varzi's Alfa Romeo 158 skidded on the wet surface, flipping over and crushing him to death.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] Varzi's death resulted in the FIA mandating the wearing of crash helmets for racing, which had been optional previously.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] In 1950 Varzi's chief mechanic, Amedeo Bignami, co-established the *Scuderia Achille Varzi* in Argentina.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] The team entered some Formula One races in 1950 equipped with Maseratis 4CL and 4CLT and featured drivers José Froilán González, Antonio Branca, Alfredo Pián and Nello Pagani.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] On 5 June 2004, Poste Italiane issued a stamp commemorating Varzi.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] Varzi was mentioned more than once in the 2023 movie, Ferrari (2023 film).
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] In 1991, motorsport journalist Giorgio Terruzzi recounted Varzi's story in a book titled *Una curva cieca – Vita di Achille Varzi*.
[src:bugatti-veyron/achille-varzi] During his career, Achille Varzi competed in 139 races, winning 33.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] In aeronautics, **air brakes**, or **speed brakes**, are a type of flight control surface used on an aircraft to increase the drag on the aircraft.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] When extended into the airstream, air brakes cause an increase in the drag on the aircraft.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] When not in use, they conform to the local streamlined profile of the aircraft in order to help minimize drag.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] Air brakes differ from spoilers in that air brakes are designed to increase drag while making little change to lift, whereas spoilers reduce the lift-to-drag ratio and require a higher angle of attack to maintain lift, resulting in a higher stall speed.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] However, flight spoilers are routinely referred to as "speed brakes" on transport aircraft by pilots and manufacturers, despite significantly reducing lift.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] In the early decades of powered flight, air brakes were flaps mounted on the wings.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] They were manually controlled by a lever in the cockpit, and mechanical linkages to the air brake.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] Another early type of air brake, developed in 1931, was fitted to aircraft wing support struts.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] In 1936, Hans Jacobs, who headed Nazi Germany's *Deutsche Forschungsanstalt für Segelflug* (DFS) glider research organization before World War II, developed blade-style self-operating dive brakes, on the upper and lower surface of each wing, for gliders.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] Most early gliders were equipped with spoilers on the wings in order to adjust their angle of descent during approach to landing.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] More modern gliders use air brakes that may spoil lift as well as increase drag, dependent on where they are positioned.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] A British report written in 1942 discusses the need for dive brakes to enable dive bombers, torpedo bombers and fighter aircraft to meet their respective combat performance requirements and, more generally, glide-path control.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] It discusses different types of air brakes and their requirements, in particular that they should have no appreciable effect on lift or trim and how this may be achieved with split trailing edge flaps on the wings, for example.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] There was also a requirement to vent the brake surfaces using numerous perforations or slots to reduce airframe buffeting.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] A US report written in 1949 describes numerous air brake configurations, and their performance, on wings and fuselage for propeller and jet aircraft.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] Often, characteristics of both spoilers and air brakes are desirable and are combined – most modern airliner jets feature combined spoiler and air brake controls.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] On landing, the deployment of these spoilers ("lift dumpers") causes a significant reduction in wing lift, so the weight of the aircraft is transferred from the wings to the undercarriage.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] The increased weight increases the available friction force for braking.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] In addition, the form drag created by the spoilers directly assists the braking effect.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] Reverse thrust is also used to help slow the aircraft after landing.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] Virtually all jet-powered aircraft have an air brake or, in the case of most airliners, flight spoilers that also generate drag, albeit with the additional lift dumping effect.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] Propeller-driven aircraft benefit from the natural braking effect of the propeller when engine power is reduced to idle, but jet engines have no similar braking effect, so jet-powered aircraft must use air brakes to control speed and descent angle during landing approach.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] Many early jets used parachutes as air brakes on approach (Arado Ar 234, Boeing B-47) or after landing (English Electric Lightning).
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] Split-tailcone air brakes have been used on the Blackburn Buccaneer naval strike aircraft designed in the 1950s and Fokker F28 Fellowship and British Aerospace 146 airliners.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] The Buccaneer air brake, when opened, reduced the length of the aircraft in the confined space on an aircraft carrier.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] The F-15 Eagle, Sukhoi Su-27, F-18 Hornet and other fighters have an air brake located just behind the cockpit.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] The deceleron is an aileron that functions normally in flight but can split in half such that the top half goes up as the bottom half goes down to brake.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] This technique was first used on the F-89 Scorpion and has since been used by Northrop on several aircraft, including the B-2 Spirit.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] The Space Shuttle used a similar system.
[src:bugatti-veyron/air-brake-aeronautics] The vertically split rudder opened in "clamshell" fashion on landing to act as a speed brake.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] Alba's origins date from before the Roman civilization, connected probably to the presence of Celtic and Ligurian tribes in the area.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] The modern town occupies the site of ancient **Alba Pompeia**, the name given after being officially recognized as a town by the Roman consul Gnaeus Pompeius Strabo while constructing a road from Aquae Statiellae (Acqui) to Augusta Taurinorum (Turin).
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] Alba was the birthplace of Publius Helvius Pertinax, briefly Roman emperor in 193.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] After the fall of the Western Empire, the city was repeatedly sacked by Ostrogoths, Burgundians, Byzantines, Lombards, Franks, Hungarians and Saracens.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] In the 11th century it became a free commune (or city-state) and was a member of the Lombard League.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] Montferrat and the Visconti fought over the town; later it became a possession of the Gonzaga.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] Charles Emmanuel I of Savoy conquered it twice, while later France and Spain battled for its possession.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] The Treaty of Cherasco (1631) assigned Alba definitively to Savoy.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] During Napoleonic Wars, it was part of the Republic of Alba (1796) and of the Subalpine Republic, both French clients, before being annexed to the French Empire in 1802.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] It was an arrondissement center in firstly Tanaro department between 1802 and 1805, later in Stura one between 1805 and 1814 before liberation by Austrian troops.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] It was returned to the Kingdom of Sardinia (Duchy of Savoy's name after gaining Sardinia in 1720) in 1814.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] Alba won a Gold Medal for Military Valour for the heroic activity of its citizens in the Italian resistance movement during the course of World War II.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] On 10 October 1944, the town was liberated by partisans who established a Republic of Alba which for a few weeks was able to maintain its independence from the Fascist Republic of Salò.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] The republic lasted until 2 November 1944, when the Republic of Salo retook it.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] French troops finally liberated it on 2 May 1945.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] Approximately located at about 50 km from the cities of Turin and Cuneo, Alba is placed on the right side of the river Tanaro.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] The climate is typically drier than in other lands at the north of the Po river.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] Of the Roman city, which had a polygonal form, parts of the fortified gate and remains of some edifices with marble and mosaics can still be seen.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] The city museums include the Federico Eusebio Civic Museum of Archaeology and Natural Sciences.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] In addition to traditional agriculture, Alba is a very important center of wine.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] In the area of Alba, in fact, there are 290 wineries that cultivate an area of 700 hectares (1,700 acres) of land, producing an average of 61,200 hL of wine annually.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] The city has a thriving economy, boasting the confectionery industry's world-renowned Ferrero, the publishing house Società San Paolo and the textile firm Miroglio.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] The town also houses the largest cooperative credit bank of Italy, by number of partners, the Banca d'Alba, and the international food chain Eataly.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] UniEuro, the Italian chain of stores specializing in household electrical appliances and acquired by Dixons Retail in 2002, was also established in Alba.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] Alba is also famous worldwide for its white truffles, and its annual Truffle Festival.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] According to the Köppen climate classification, Alba has a humid subtropical climate which is moderated by the proximity of the Mediterranean sea.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] Its winters are warmer, January is usually 5 °C (41 °F), and its summers are hot, when temperatures can reach 35 °C (95 °F).
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] Rain falls mostly during the spring and autumn; during the hottest months rain is less common, July with 43 mm (2 in) and August with 51 mm (2 in).
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] During November and December, the town of Alba can be prone to fog.
[src:bugatti-veyron/alba-piedmont] The town's football club Albese has been in existence since 1917.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] Brembo was established in Paladina, Italy, on January 11, 1961, by Emilio Bombassei and Italo Breda (father and uncle, respectively, to the current Chairman Alberto Bombassei).
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] The company was named after the Brembo river.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] Bombassei lived in a village on the coast of the river before moving to Milan.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] Soon after Brembo was formed, it specialized in disc brakes, which were imported from the UK at the time.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] The company entered into a supply contract with Alfa Romeo in 1964 and became Moto Guzzi's brake component supplier in 1966.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] In the 1980s, Brembo also began supplying brakes to BMW, Chrysler, Ferrari, Mercedes-Benz, Nissan, and Porsche.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] Brembo went public on the Milan Stock Exchange in 1995.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] In 2000, Brembo purchased the UK-based racing brake and clutch manufacturer AP Racing (a former division of Automotive Products).
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] On November 9, 2007, Brembo's North American subsidiary acquired the Automotive Brake Components division of Hayes Lemmerz.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] The approximately €39.6-million sale included approximately 250 employees and production facilities in Homer, Michigan and Apodaca, Mexico.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] An official press release on May 21, 2014, announced an €83-million expansion of the Michigan facility.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] Later that year, on December 2, Brembo also announced plans to invest €32 million into a 31,500-square-meter production facility, projected to produce two million aluminum calipers annually.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] The expectation was initial operation by 2016 and full operation by the end of 2018.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] On March 5, 2015, Brembo's deputy chairman, Matteo Tiraboschi, reported the company's 2014 sales growth of 15% up to €1.8 billion and a net profit increase of 45% to €129.1 million.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] He also reported the company was exploring acquiring assets, with a focus on the automotive and aviation sectors.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] The company's corporate headquarters are in Stezzano, and the company has more than 10,634 employees within Italy and at branches in Brazil, China, Japan, Mexico, Poland, Spain, Sweden, the UK and the US.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] As of 2019, Brembo was present in 14 countries worldwide.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] In October 2024, Brembo acquired Öhlins Racing for $405 million.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] Brembo specializes in performance braking systems and components as well as conducting research on braking systems.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] Brembo sells over 1,300 products worldwide and is known for their aftermarket automotive brake components, including calipers, drums, rotors, and brake lines.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] Brembo owns the foundries that produce their initial materials and supply the manufacturing plants.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] In all other markets, the company controls the entire production system—from raw materials through distribution.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] The company holds QS9000 and ISO 9001 certifications.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] Brembo is the braking systems provider for Formula One.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] Brembo also supplies the majority of MotoGP teams; the Gresini squad used Nissin brakes during the 2014 season and later Brembo returned again as a single brake package partner and supplier in MotoGP by 2016.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] Brembo was also an official brake supplier for the IndyCar Series from the 2012 season until the 2016 season; during the 2017 season, Brembo supplied calipers only.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] During the next season, Brembo supplied entire braking systems to all Spark Racing Technology Gen2 cars in Formula E.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] Since 2005, Brembo has been an official brake caliper supplier for the GP2 Series and the FIA Formula 2 Championship.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] Since 2010, Brembo has been an official whole brake supplier for the GP3 Series and the FIA Formula 3 Championship.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] Brembo is the exclusive supplier of braking systems for the MotoE World Cup.
[src:bugatti-veyron/ap-racing] Brembo Is the official technology partner for the sim racing series Gran Turismo and has various braking systems that can be used in game such as carbon-ceramic brakes and Brembo calipers.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The **Bugatti Veyron EB 16.4** is a mid-engine sports car designed and developed in Germany by the Volkswagen Group and Bugatti, and manufactured in Molsheim, France by French automobile manufacturer Bugatti.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] It was named after the racing driver Pierre Veyron.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The original version has a top speed of 407 km/h (253 mph).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] It was named the 2000s Car of the Decade by the BBC television programme *Top Gear*.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The standard Veyron also won *Top Gear*'s Best Car Driven All Year award in 2005.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Super Sport version of the Veyron is one of the fastest street-legal production cars in the world, with a top speed of 431.072 km/h (267.856 mph).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Veyron Grand Sport Vitesse was the fastest roadster in the world, reaching an averaged top speed of 408.84 km/h (254.04 mph) in a test on 6 April 2013.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The production car speed record was later taken by another Bugatti, the Chiron, and then often changed hands for a while.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Veyron's chief designer was Hartmut Warkuß, with the exterior being designed by Jozef Kabaň of Volkswagen.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Much of the engineering work was conducted under the guidance of chief technical officer Wolfgang Schreiber.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Veyron includes a sound system designed and built by Burmester Audiosysteme.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Several special variants have been produced.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] In December 2010, Bugatti began offering prospective buyers the ability to customise exterior and interior colours by using the *Veyron 16.4 Configurator* application on the marque's official website.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Bugatti Veyron was discontinued in late 2014, but special edition models continued to be produced until 2015.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] In May 1998, Volkswagen AG acquired the rights to use the Bugatti logo and the trade name Bugatti Automobiles S.A.S.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] To succeed the EB 110 model produced under the previous ownership, the automaker quickly released a series of concept cars whose technological advancements would culminate in the form of the Veyron 16.4.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Between October 1998 and September 1999, Bugatti introduced a series of Giugiaro-designed concept vehicles, each with permanent four-wheel drive and powered by the Volkswagen-designed W18 engine.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The first car, the EB 118, was a 2-door luxury coupé presented at the 1998 Paris Motor Show.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The next car, the EB 218, was a 4-door saloon presented at the 1999 Geneva Motor Show.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The third and final car, the 18/3 Chiron, was a mid-engine sports car presented at the 1999 International Motor Show in Frankfurt.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] In October 1999, Bugatti unveiled a fourth concept car at the Tokyo Motor Show.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The EB 18/4 Veyron was a mid-engine sports car styled in-house under the direction of Hartmut Warkuß.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] In 2000, a modified version, the EB 16/4 Veyron, was displayed at motor shows in Detroit, Geneva, and Paris.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Rather than the three-bank W18 engine of the four previous concept cars, the EB 16/4 featured the four-bank W16 engine architecture installed in every production example of the Veyron.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Warkuß also commissioned SEAT head of design, Walter de Silva, to submit a design proposal for the new Bugatti.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The design was ultimately rejected in favour of Warkuß's own proposal.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The decision to start production of the car was made by the Volkswagen Group in 2001.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The first roadworthy prototype was completed in August 2003.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] It is identical to the later series variant, except for a few details.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] In the transition from development to series production, considerable technical problems had to be addressed, repeatedly delaying production until September 2005.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Veyron EB 16.4 is named in honor of Pierre Veyron, a Bugatti development engineer, test driver and company race driver who, with co-driver Jean-Pierre Wimille, won the 1939 24 Hours of Le Mans while driving a Bugatti.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The "EB" refers to Bugatti founder Ettore Bugatti and the "16.4" refers to the engine's 16 cylinders and quad-turbochargers.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Veyron features an 8.0-litre, quad-turbocharged, W16 cylinder engine, equivalent to two narrow-angle V8 engines bolted together.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Each cylinder has four valves for a total of 64, but the configuration of each bank allows two overhead camshafts to drive two banks of cylinders so only four camshafts are needed.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The engine is fed by four turbochargers and displaces 7,993 cc (487.8 cu in), with a square 86 by 86 mm (3.39 by 3.39 in) bore and stroke.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Veyron can be driven in either semi-automatic or fully-automatic mode.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] A replacement transmission for the Veyron costs just over US$120,000.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] It also has permanent all-wheel drive using the Haldex Traction system.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] It uses special Michelin PAX run-flat tyres, designed specifically to accommodate the Veyron's top speed, and cost US$25,000 per set.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The tyres can be mounted on the wheels only in France, a service which costs US$70,000.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] This gives the car a power-to-weight ratio, according to Volkswagen Group's figures, of 530 PS (390 kW; 523 hp) per ton.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] It has a drag coefficient of *C**d*=0.41 (normal condition) and *C**d*=0.36 (after lowering to the ground), and a frontal area of 2.07 m2 (22.3 sq ft).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] This gives it a drag area, the product of drag coefficient and frontal area, of *C*dA=0.74 m2 (8.0 sq ft).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Despite the exclusivity of the project and the price of each unit, used existing components from VW Group models or other suppliers (hydraulic pump, air filter, etc.).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] This is acceptable in mechanical engineering, but can lead to rapid wear due to heavy loads of the Veyron, which, however, simplifies independent repairs.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] According to Volkswagen Group and certified by TÜV Süddeutschland, the W16 engine utilised by the Veyron has a power output of 736 kW (987 hp; 1,001 PS), and generates 1,250 N⋅m (922 lbf⋅ft) of torque.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] German inspection officials recorded an average top speed of the original version at 408.47 km/h (253.81 mph) during test sessions on Volkswagen Group's private Ehra-Lessien test track on 19 April 2005.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] This top speed was almost matched by James May on *Top Gear* in November 2006, at the Ehra-Lessien test track, at 407.5 km/h (253.2 mph).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] May noted that at top speed the engine consumes 45,000 L (9,900 imp gal) of air per minute (as much as a human breathes in four days).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Back in the *Top Gear* studio, co-presenter Jeremy Clarkson commented that most sports cars felt like they were shaking apart at their top speed, and asked May if that was the case with the Veyron at 407 km/h (253 mph).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] May responded that the Veyron was very controlled, and only wobbled slightly when the air brake deployed.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] In regular use, the ability to reach the above absolute top speed is locked out.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The car's normal top speed is listed as 343 km/h (213 mph).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Also, when the car reaches 220 km/h (137 mph), hydraulics lower the car until it has a ground clearance of about 9 cm (3.5 in).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] At the same time, the wing and spoiler deploy.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] In this *handling mode*, the wing provides 3,425 newtons (770 lbf) of downforce, holding the car to the road.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] To reach the car's absolute top speed, its *top speed mode* must be entered while the vehicle is at rest.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] For this, the driver must use a special top speed key in a keyhole to the left of their seat, which triggers a checklist to establish whether the car and its driver are ready to attempt to reach 407 km/h (253 mph).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] If so, the rear spoiler retracts, the front air diffusers shut, and normal 12.5 cm (4.9 in) ground clearance drops to 6.5 cm (2.6 in).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Veyron's brakes use cross drilled, radially vented carbon fibre reinforced silicon carbide (C/SiC) composite discs, manufactured by SGL Carbon, which have less brake fade and weigh less than standard cast iron discs.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The lightweight aluminium alloy monobloc brake calipers are made by AP Racing; the front have eight titanium pistons and the rear calipers have six pistons.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Bugatti claims maximum deceleration of 1.3 g on road tyres.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] As an added safety feature, in the event of brake failure, an anti-lock braking system (ABS) has also been installed on the handbrake.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Prototypes have been subjected to repeated 1.0 g braking from 312 km/h (194 mph) to 80 km/h (50 mph) without fade.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] With the car's acceleration from 80 km/h (50 mph) to 312 km/h (194 mph), that test can be performed every 22 seconds.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] At speeds above 200 km/h (124 mph), the rear wing also acts as an airbrake, snapping to a 55° angle in 0.4 seconds once brakes are applied, providing an additional 0.68 g (6.66 m/s2) of deceleration (equivalent to the stopping power of an ordinary hatchback).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Bugatti claims the Veyron will brake from 400 km/h (249 mph) to a standstill in less than 10 seconds, though distance covered in this time will be half a kilometre (third of a mile).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The targa top version of the Bugatti Veyron EB 16.4, dubbed the Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Grand Sport, was unveiled at the 2008 Pebble Beach Concours d'Elegance.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] It has extensive reinforcements to compensate for the lack of a standard roof and small changes to the windshield and running lights.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Two removable tops are included, the second a temporary arrangement fashioned after an umbrella.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The top speed with the hardtop in place is the same as the standard coupé version, but with the roof removed is limited to 369 km/h (229 mph)—and to 130 km/h (81 mph) with the temporary soft roof.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Grand Sport edition was limited to 150 units, with the first 50 going exclusively to registered Bugatti customers.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Production began in the second quarter of 2009.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Super Sport is a faster, more powerful version of the Bugatti Veyron 16.4.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Super Sport has increased engine power output of 1,200 PS (882 kW; 1,183 hp) at 6,400 rpm and a maximum torque of 1,500 N⋅m (1,106 lb⋅ft) at 3,000–5,000 rpm and a revised aerodynamic package.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Super Sport has been driven as fast as 431.072 km/h (267.856 mph), making it the fastest production road car in the world at the time of its introduction although it is electronically limited to 415 km/h (258 mph) to protect the tyres from disintegrating.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Super Sport World Record Edition is a version of the Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Super Sport.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] It has an orange body detailing, orange wheels, and a special black exposed carbon body.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The electronic limiter is deactivated on this version.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The model was unveiled in 2010 at The Quail, followed by the 2010 Monterey Historic Races at Laguna Seca, and the 2010 Pebble Beach Concours d'Elegance.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] On 4 July 2010, James May, a television presenter on BBC Two's television show *Top Gear*, drove the Veyron Super Sport on Volkswagen's Ehra-Lessien (near Wolfsburg, Germany) high-speed test track at 417.61 km/h (259.49 mph).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Later that day, Bugatti's official test driver Pierre Henri Raphanel drove the Super Sport version of the Veyron at the same track to establish the car's top speed.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] When the record was certified it was already well known to the public that the customer car would be electronically limited to 415 km/h (258 mph).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Yet, after a query by the *Sunday Times* Guinness' PR director Jaime Strang was quoted on 5 April 2013: "As the car's speed limiter was deactivated, this modification was against the official guidelines.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] On 15 April 2013, Bugatti's speed record was confirmed: "Following a thorough review conducted with a number of external experts, Guinness World Records is pleased to announce the confirmation of Bugatti's record of Fastest production car achieved by the Veyron 16.4 SuperSport.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The focus of the review was with respect to what may constitute a modification to a car's standard specification.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Grand Sport Vitesse is a targa top version of the Veyron Super Sport.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The engine in the Vitesse variant has a maximum power output of 1,200 PS (882 kW; 1,183 bhp) at 6,400 rpm and a maximum torque of 1,500 N⋅m (1,100 lb⋅ft) at 3,000–5,000 rpm.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] These figures allow the car to accelerate from a stand still to 100 km/h (62 mph) in 2.6 seconds.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] On normal roads, the Vitesse is electronically limited to 375 km/h (233 mph).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Vitesse was first unveiled at the 2012 Geneva Motor Show and later at the 2012 Beijing Auto Show and the 2012 São Paulo Motor Show.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] In 2013, Bugatti produced a series of Vitesse dedicated to racing legends, including Jean-Pierre Wimille, Jean Bugatti, Meo Costantini, and Ettore Bugatti.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] A Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Grand Sport Vitesse driven by the Chinese racing driver Anthony Liu at Volkswagen Group's proving grounds in Ehra-Lessien became the fastest open-top production sports car, with a top speed of 408.84 km/h (254.04 mph).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Wolfgang Schreiber, President of Bugatti Automobiles S.A.S, said "When we introduced the Vitesse, we established the top speed for open-top driving to be 375 km/h.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Still, we could not let go of the idea of reaching the 400 km/h mark with this car as well.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Bugatti Veyron Linea Vincero is a Veyron 16.4 modified by the German car modification firm Mansory.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Linea Vincero has new wheel rims and new exterior lower bodywork.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] It extensively uses carbon fibre in the interior and exterior as well.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] This car, with its interior and exterior customisations, is worth US$1 million more than a standard Veyron 16.4.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Bugatti Veyron Linea D'oro is a car made on the basis of the Veyron Grand Sport and the 16.4 by the German car modification firm Mansory.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The D'oro's exterior design is identical to its predecessor's but it has a few differences such as the gold paint on the badge, rims and other features.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The iconic V-shaped badge is also present on this car's front grille.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Bugatti Veyron Linea Viviere (commonly known as the Mansory Viviere) is a car made on the basis of the Bugatti Veyron Super Sport by the German car modification firm Mansory.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] This car's exterior design features the iconic V-shaped front grille and an additional exhaust system below its rear lights.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The interior has been handcrafted and carbon fibre has been extensively used.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] This car has a second generation known as the Viviere Diamond Edition which has been made on the same basis.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] This car is the final Veyron Edition tuned by Mansory and has a marble coloured exterior paintwork.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Bugatti Veyron Linea Viviere costs US$2.3 million, making it one of the most expensive Veyrons ever produced.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] As of 6 August 2014, 405 cars had been produced and delivered to customers worldwide, with orders that have already been placed for another 30.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Bugatti was reported to produce 300 coupés and 150 roadsters up to the end of 2015.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Production amounted to 450 units in a span of over 10 years.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The final production vehicle, a Grand Sport Vitesse titled "La Finale" (The Last One), was displayed at the Geneva Motor Show from 5–15 March 2015.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] In 2008, Bugatti then-CEO Dr Franz-Josef Paefgen confirmed that the Veyron would be replaced by another high-end model by 2012.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The successor to the Veyron was unveiled in concept form as the Bugatti Vision Gran Turismo at the September 2015 Frankfurt Motor Show.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] A toned-down version of the radically styled Vision Gran Turismo concept car, now called the Chiron, debuted at the March 2016 Geneva Motor Show.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Production started in 2017 and production was limited to 500 units, with the final Chiron being produced in May 2024.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] All three former presenters of the popular BBC motoring show *Top Gear* have given the Veyron considerable praise.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] While initially skeptical that the Veyron would ever be produced, Jeremy Clarkson later declared the Veyron "the greatest car ever made and the greatest car we will ever see in our lifetime", comparing it to Concorde and S.S.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] He noted that the production cost of a Veyron was £5 million, but was sold to customers for just £1 million.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Volkswagen designed the car merely as a technical exercise.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] James May described the Veyron as "our Concorde moment".
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Clarkson test drove the Veyron from Alba in northern Italy to London in a race against May and Richard Hammond who made the journey in a Cessna 182 aeroplane.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] A few episodes later, May drove the Veyron at the VW test track and took it to its top speed of 407.16 km/h (253.00 mph).
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] In series 10, Hammond raced the Veyron against the Eurofighter Typhoon and lost.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] He also raced the car in Series 13 against a McLaren F1 driven by The Stig in a one-mile (1.6 km) drag race in Abu Dhabi.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The commentary focused on Bugatti's "amazing technical achievement" versus the "non-gizmo" racing purity of the F1.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] While the F1 was quicker off the line and remained ahead until both cars were travelling at approximately 200 km/h (124 mph), the Bugatti overtook its competitor from 200 to 300 km/h (124 to 186 mph) and emerged the victor.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Hammond has stated that he did not use the Veyron's launch control in order to make the race more interesting.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The Veyron also won the award for "Car of the Decade" in *Top Gear*'s end of 2010 award show.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Clarkson commented, "It was a car that just rewrote the rule book really, an amazing piece of engineering, a genuine Concorde moment".
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] When the standard version was tested in 2008, it did not reach the top of the lap time leader board, with a time of 1:18.3, which was speculated as being due to the car's considerable weight disadvantage against the other cars towards the top.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] In 2011, Martin Roach's book *Bugatti Veyron: A Quest for Perfection – The Story of the Greatest Car in the World* took the stance that the car had now become so famous that it is effectively a bona fide celebrity.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] The book follows its author as he attempts to track down and drive the car, along the way interviewing chief designers, test drivers, and the president of Bugatti.
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] During its development period McLaren F1 designer Gordon Murray said in UK auto magazine *Evo*: "The most pointless exercise on the planet has got to be this four-wheel-drive, thousand-horsepower Bugatti." But after driving it he called it "a huge achievement".
[src:bugatti-veyron/bugatti-veyron] Murray was impressed with the Veyron's engine and transmission after he test drove one for *Road & Track* magazine.
